76561197999385566,Recommended,268500,21087762,"Posted: 9 February, 2016",all,redshadovv,"XCOM 2 is essentially XCOM 1 with everything dialed up a notch. The short of it is that if you liked and played XCOM 1 for any significant amount of time then you are almost guaranteed to enjoy XCOM 2.Great new additions or significant improvements:RNG:The huge role random chance played in the core mechanics of XCOM 1 was something that really bothered me and many other players. Thankfully, in this iteration, there are so many more ways of dealing guaranteeing damage that it is relatively simple to mitigate RNG almost completely with the appropriate style of play. A few things allow this: first off more abilities that are guaranteed to deal damage including combat protocol on the specialist and weapon upgrades that deal dmg on missed shots, cover is more destructible this time around which allows you to easily expose enemies for reliable shots and most importantly the way the game works now allows and even encourages aggressive flanking. It is not uncommon to get 90-100% shot success on most missions mid way through the campaign now as a result.Aggression and overwatch spam:Due to the way the maps were configured and the constant threat of activating additional groups of enemies, a very defense oriented and overwatch centered tactical play style was considered optimal in XCOM 1. This is entirely not the case in XCOM 2. The way the maps are setup now, it feels like you have much more room to maneuver around the map without fatally exposing your squad. With the concealment mechanic which lets you sneak up on the aliens and with the presence of turn limits on many more missions this time around, the game actually encourages an aggressive playstyle where you take out enemy groups with 1-2 turns of activating them through aggressive flanking and, as is my preference, heavy use of explosives. Another important aspect of this is that using explosives no longer equates to losing the loot you desperately need to fund your operations. It’s a little bit more complicated than that but generally speaking you don’t have to stress so much about not blowing up the aliens this time around.Additional customization options:I really wasn’t into tweaking the appearance of my soldiers in XCOM 1 that much but with the mind blowing amount of customization options available now, I’m really getting attached to some of my soldiers that I’ve decked out to look badass. The character pool system which lets saved soldiers randomly appear in your campaign as recruits or VIPs or scientists and engineers is also quite brilliant and unexpected allowing for favorite soldiers to effortlessly reappear in a new campaign. With the out of the box support for mods through steam workshop, the already staggering number of options will only grow.Things which are problematic:Unresponsiveness:I had this complaint with XCOM 1 as well. What I’m talking about is how the game loves to take control away from you in the middle of the action, locking the camera and disabling input while it makes you stare at a “new” enemy that you’ve already seen before accompanied by Central or the Doctor essentially telling you what you most likely already know. There is seemingly more of that this time around and some abilities, in particular gremlin abilities on the specialist have unnecessarily long animations for you to endure. Some of this also applies to the UI in the macro game (the avenger and geoscape). Transferring from the geoscape to the armory menu for instance, take entirely too long and clicking while the animation is in progress may end up sending you to another menu accidentally which only serves to frustrate the matter more.UI streamlining:In the course of trying to make the UI less dense, a lot of useful information has been buried further down in menus. This leads to a lot of unnecessary clicking to find important bits of information and makes comparing some stats across soldiers unjustifiably painful. The biggest culprit of course, is not being able to see vital soldier stats side by side across soldiers, including their hp and what upgrades they have installed on themselves and their gear. There are several other places where the streamlined approach makes information difficult to discern or understand due to ambiguity, but all this one can get used to eventually, even though some frustration will be encountered along the way. I suspect this is once again a symptom of PC games being constrained by a UI designed for a controller. It’s not a major gripe, but it is something which should have been improved in this iteration and not the other way around as it stands now."
,Recommended,268500,21110808,"Posted: 10 February, 2016",all,(YouTube)Dragnix,"Target Audience:Tactical Combat Fans that want a challenge, and don't have beefs with the RNG gods.Review Video:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dsQH16fF9DcSummary:The game that has everything going for it as a sequel to one of the best reborn franchises of the last 5 years.....with one huge exception. The tactical combat from the original returns with some additional units and mechanics that takes it to the next level. The small changes like additional focus on timed missions helped the game in the big picture a lot, and the improved balance/skill trees made every class a great boon in the right situation. The simulation portion of the game may have been streamlined....but it was for the better in my opinion, as it makes an impact on your combat performance directly. The visuals for the most part are nice, although it will take you out the experience as well with some bad glitches. The story makes a bit more sense this time around and while its filled with scifi tropes, it does the job. This would be a shoe-in purchase if the performance issues, load times, and glitches are taken care of, because they REALLY create a major problem in the end, as I would have stopped playing if I wasn't formal reviewing the game. If you've got a backlog: play through it first, and wait for some of the issues to be fixed.Lists:My Positives:The well known combat is still as good as ever, with incremental improvements. Difficult but smartly put together.Class balance seems to be there a bit more this time around..Psy operatives were useful and still strong, but a great grenadier or ranger could give them a run for their money.Simulation elements wisely refined, and seemed to make the difference in the battle in the long run.Like the addition of more timed missions: it forces  less conservative play, and put your units more in danger, but not to the point where it was unwinnable.Great character customization added that makes the sting of losing a soldier that much harder, when you've put the effort in crafting them from the bottom up. Your soldiers also can have a nice in-game personality that actually shows up in the lines.Great move on Firaxis part to put in mod support on day one. I expect a lot to be done, as there's a lot of potential in the various weapons/units/etc.The secondary equipment makes a huge difference this time around, and there was actually huge reasons to take it along as opposed to another med pack.Improved visuals, in particular with character designs. Like the simple yet effective designs of the Viper and the Gatekeeper.For those who really want it, Firaxis put several autosaves in there at the start of a mission and last turn. If you're a cheater. Cause it's cheating.My Negatives:Hate, hate the new graze system. It adds an element to combat that you don't know what it directly does in terms of percent probability for it to happen, and is generally an unknown factor. It's the one thing you don't know, and it will REALLY get on your nerves.Panic system seems to mean less then before.Held together by glue and string, it seems. The game can run great at times, but when something goes wrong, bad things happen to not only the performance, but the in game mechanics get messed with as well. It's unstable.The loading times. My god the loading times. At one point, it took 3 minutes,  27 seconds to load into the next portion of the game. Unoptimized, the game is not.Glitch Fest 2000. Hits a wide spectrum of issues, from graphical, to camera, to in-game affecting. Takes you right of the experience. It's funny at times....but really annoying at others. Especially when the camera decides to show you a wall because it can't figure out jack♥♥♥♥♥♥The music doesn't do the job like the original. It just doesn't have the punch, it's good....but compared to the original, it just doesn't work at ALL."
76561198197517446,Recommended,268500,30891671,Posted: 1 April,all,Hunter,"Okay. So i played the crap out of this game. As you can see at my play hours.I understood and learned a bunch of things about it, so let's get started:The game takes place 20 years after the Defeat of XCOM in the original game, going from a timeline where they lost their base at the hands on the alien Invasion. From there, they now work at a salvaged Alien Ship, from the looks of it seems to be one of the Heavy class ship of old. Earth is now subjugated and you are the leader of the resistance forces who fight against their rule. You, the Commander, must fight back against a new and sinister enemy know as ADVENT, an governemnt organization created by the Coalition between humans and the Alien Elders, while trying to stop a secret project that could be the end of mankind.GAMEPLAY ASPECTS and thoughts on it:> The RNG and POSITIONING-Tactical based gameplay similar to the original game, but improved. More organized than the previous titles.It requires not only strategic thinking to turn odds to your favor, but also a little bit of luck in a RNG dice roll. That said, the RNG is heavily influenced by how you are positioned and protected.You will not hit every shot, and the aliens can hit you with some lucky shots, however both of you are governed by the same rules, with the veteran difficulty balancing the tip towards your favor with ""Miss Streaks"" and ""Aim Assists"" for your soldiers. At higher difficulties, those differences cease, you and the aliens obey the same odds.A bad positioning effectively means your defeat, and a strong positioning can lead you to victory. Keep that in mind while playing and you will find yourself depending less on luck and more in how you place your troops. (It may happen the hilarious 95% chance miss, it's not frequent and quite rare, unless the game really decided to hate you all of a sudden).> SKILLS and ABILITIES-Abilities are important, as they can bless you with guaranteed hits you will definetly need in some situations. It can turn the tide of battles very quickly to your favor. That said, the enemy can do the very same things with their abilities should the circunstances present themselves. Two units close to each may result in a grenade flying towards you. Or one of the powerful abilities the aliens have may be used against you.With that in mind you will understand that some aliens must be taken out first, or that will result in one of your troopers being dragged across the map or half of your squad poisoned.Different Aliens mean different aproach and different strategies, learn your enemy in order to defeat them.> CLASSES and PROGRESS- There are effectively 4 default classes for your troops with 1 special class divided in two ability trees that give them different roles in combat, the abilities can be mixed, so you are not stuck with just one role or the other, and given the proper infrastructure, you can retrain them (although you cannot change their class)- The Aliens do have different types of enemies with different abilities, however their upgrades are based around the progression know as ""force level"" and ""Dark Events"".-> The force level effectively defines the type of alien you will face, as well as the upgrades towards aliens you already encounter. A common trooper will become and Advanced trooper as the time moves forward, and later in the game you will be facing Elite level troopers and more powerful Aliens.-> Dark Events are strategic elements that rule over your campaign, they can last 1 to 2 months depending on the Event, or add points to their secret project. They can range from adding poison coated ammo to your enemies, or sent a UFO to hunt your SHIP.>RESEARCH:The research element is straight to the point, have a material, research it. Have a corpse, autopsy it. Have a thing, do this thing. You can improve your research time with more scientists.>ENGINEERING:Also straight to the point. You research a thing, you acquired a blueprint on that thing, you build that thing.With the exception on the proving grounds, where takes time to construct an armor or make said blueprint. Experimental item blueprints give you a random item that can make a hell of a difference in your performance. Or building an more advanced armor that is not the default medium choice.-TIP-Research and Engineering can save you if you had your star squad wiped by a couple of bad decisions, however, losing missions over and over may result in campaign victory for the aliens, and you falling behind in force level category, where there's simply no way for you to face them anymore without you effectively turning a simple encounter into an epic struggle between untrained troops and powerful alien overlords.Which most of the time will result in Death if you are not of the most experienced XCOM player.That said, these elements make an realistic representation in technology gap, if you don't keep up with your enemy, you will get steam rolled across the battlefield. It also means that if you manage to get the Early advantage in boosting your crew Engineers and Scientist staff, you will effectively do the same thing to them, although it all comes down in how you manage your squad into battle. Once you get the hang of it, you will rarely lose a mission, maybe a soldier or two.>STORYLINE MISSIONS and OBJECTIVES:- There are a couple of missions that represent the Storyline progression, which are required to complete in order to reach the end and win the game. Some have the term of ""catasthropical failure"", which results in instant victory for the aliens should you lose it. Missions with that term allow you to restart it and try again, or restart the game with a new campaign. One of the two.--------- In regards to DLC -----------Alien Hunters:- This DLC adds four new powerful itens and three new powerful aliens for you to face along your campaign. With a story element should you decide to have the complete.-> Having the story mode selected you will have a mission that starts the scenario, the enemies will not appear until you decide to.-> Not having the story mode selected results in the enemies appearing normaly in the campaign and the weapons appearing in the engineering section for you to build them.Shen's last gift:- This DLC adds a MEC to your squad. An early game useless unit but a late game monster with the technological improvements. Like the Alien Hunters, it does have an story element that allows you to start the DLC. If not selected, you will be able to build it as soon as you get the Proving grounds.Anarchy's Children:- A cosmetic DLC, it adds anarchy themed cosmetics to the game for you soldiers customization. The flavour is not for everyone and honestly, you can find better mods for your cosmetics. Although it has a cool piece here and there, it doesn't justify a DLC.Resistance warrior pack:- Another cosmetic DLC, that in it's size, doesn't justify a DLC. And for some reason is not included in the reinforcement pack.------- Personal suggestion for developers --------If you are planning on making a DLC for the game, i would suggest one where we could play as the Aliens in their Storyline, it seems that it has a room for expansion and will allow for a different perspective. It would introduce an different aspect to the game since the we would be playing on the Aliens Side. and will allow for some player to have a choice to subjugate humanity, or not, depending what the aliens are really thinking.It seems like a silly suggestion but it has room for potential if done correctly.------- Overall ---------It's a game that is supposed to be Brutal and unforgiving on combat side, any early mistake can lead to a defeat. It does get easier over time as you progress, but even so, it's not for casual or newbies that can't learn from their mistakes. Although Veterans can have a very casual experience.Overall.8 / 10 for Gameplay. 7 / 10 for Strategy. 4 / 10 for DLC. 7 / 10 for Story."
