,Recommended,268500,21107081,"Posted: 10 February, 2016",all,乇乂ㄒ尺卂 ㄒ卄丨匚匚,"""We are extremely impressed with XCOM 2 project thus far, Firaxis. Your recent results were beyond my expectations... And that is not a statement i make lightly.""While i have a small number of grievances here and there, they are fairly minor in comparison. With the recent games Starships and Beyond Earth, i was afraid Firaxis might've lost their touch. Though Beyond Earth was pretty decent, it was no near as fun, deep or satisfying as CiV5. XCOM 2 however restored my faith.Truly, XCOM 2 cranks its predecessor up to 11. As your opponents have grown in power and unpredictability, there's an even stronger reason to fear what potential weapon they might unleash upon you next. However, so have you. Everything feels powerful, dangerous and there's few things as satisfying as scoring a critical hit and watching a 3 meters tall monstrosity get blown away from a shotgun round. Though performance seems to be a littly wonky at times (framerate drops when in the Avenger or when deploying a flashbang grenade), it's been fairly stable for me with no bugs aside from the AI suddenly going idle once. For 16 hours of playtime on a newly released game, that's a pretty good thing in my book.Excellent production values shine everywhere. This is apparent in the smaller details as well, such as the great soundtrack and voice acting, soldier customization and the excellent atmosphere in map design that truly gives you a dystopian feel.Not to mention that XCOM2 has an amazingly badass Workshop. Where The Long War was pretty much the best alternative for the original, there's already a bunch of sweet stuff for you to go on, the game is really built to last on a strong mod community - while still providing a base game that's filled to the brim with content.The only thing, gameplay wise that bothers me is that they've added a turn limit. You must complete the objective before the timer runs out, which is usually pretty tight. Though it gives off a feeling of hurry, anxiety and fear - for a game that's partially built on chance and tactics, it's frustrating and doesn't fit well. Thankfully there are mods in the Workshop that remove or increase the turn limit, of which the latter one i highly recommend using. While this is the biggest issue i have, it can be avoided entirely, so i guess it's not much to bother with.In conclusion, any fan of XCOM or TBS will love it. Hell, i think anyone will enjoy it. And i have some very high hopes for the expansion and modding community. Possible GOTY!Edit: Seems performance issues are something some people are running into. None here, surprisingly, since nearly every game that's currently being released is full of bugs and performance issues. However, in my experience, XCOM 2 runs smoothly and without problems. Still, i would highly recommend taking proper precautions, such as giving the game's bug forum a read before picking up the game."
