,Recommended,268500,30628649,Posted: 19 March,all,[2o2p] OrDaned,"LIke its predecessor, XCOM 2 maintains a feeling of constant pressure -- every decision at every level seems weighty. Each time you move a soldier, every shot taken, each upgrade chosen, every choice at both the tactical and strategic level feels important. Every moment in the game is tense and exciting.Sometimes the random elements of the game can feel unforgiving -- missing a shot that has a 95% chance to hit always feels like you've been robbed, even though you're told explictly that the shot has a 1 in 20 chance of failing -- but sometimes the RNG also blesses you with a squad-saving bit of luck just when you need it.The story doesn't contain any surprises, but is well done. I especially enjoyed the little bits of banter in the Avenger view, especially Shen's quip about the Advent burgers. Art and sound design are both high quality; there's an occasional glitch in animation, but that's something forgivable considering that levels are procedurally generated and contain destructive elements -- every so often, you'll have a camera angle on a character that just looks odd. I mention it only out of completeness; it is rare, and never took away from the enjoyment of the game.Finally, the mod support is excellent -- many people have expanded the interface (everyone should get Overwatch All and Evac All), weapon options, new map options, and of course the Long War 2 project might as well be a completely new game by itself.Between the supurb base game and the excellent mod community, XCOM 2 will give fans of tactical games many hours of enormous fun."
