,Not Recommended,268500,21011335,"Posted: 6 February, 2016",all,The Technomancer,"I can't recommend this game.  It's no longer a strategy game, just a race against XCOM's legendary rage-inducing RNG.There's so much here to build on, and that's part of that makes this so disappointing.  There's a great stealth mechanic...that you can't use because of the turn timer, so you blow it on the opening group of enemies you see.  It's neat, fun to play with for a few (failed) missions, then you leave it alone because the turn timer invalidates a piece of great design.There's awesome classes with neat abilities...except sharpshooters are worthless since using them like the sniper they're supposed to be means that you lose them when the evac timer runs out.  Once again, the turn timer invalidates another piece of some really good class/game design.You could always counter the whims of the RNG in XCOM: EU/EW by playing safe with overwatch and setting up a good sniper position, and you can see the design intent to stop that with the turn timer.  But that turn timer coupled with the whimsical RNG turns the game from a ""series of interesting decisions"" into a series of bad ones and worse ones.It's really close to being the GOTY candidate so many reviewers are making it out to be.  But without a balance pass, it's just an overengineered race against a timer full of nigh-impossible missions.  Any strategy is invalidated by the timer, so you just roll your shots and hope they hit, because if they don't, you're dead.This is XCOM.  They don't hit often enough to stop you from dying."
76561198038944614,Not Recommended,268500,21113273,"Posted: 10 February, 2016",all,Ardents,"Summary:All in all, I'd love to have given the game a recommendation, but in it's current state, I'd rather recommend any reader to rather go play XCOM EW with long war mod or X-COM Apocalypse.Edit: It should be mentioned that XCOM 2 is far from a bad game. Also, some of the drawbacks of the game can be altered with mods like ""Stop wasting my time"", ""True concealment"" and ""Shut up Bradford"".Review:I've been looking forward to XCOM 2, while also dropping most of the PR about the game in it's developmentphase.The game adds an interesting continuation of the story from XCOM EU/EW and while the premises of the game is different from the endring of XCOM EU/EW, this is allowed for by events in the game.In XCOM 2, the aliens are in control and the remnants of the XCOM organization is in shambles and beeing hunted. Your task is to build up a strikeforce and connections around the world, work against the alien propaganda, discover what the aliens are up to and sabotage said plans.Positives:The premise of the game is positive. The aliens have conquered earth using overwhelming force, XCOM is shattered and the population is under strict control and anti-freedomfighter propaganda.Destructible terrain. I loved playing X-COM Apocalypse and beeing able to destroy pretty much anything, if needed or wanted. This is also the case in XCOM 2, where most terrain can be destroyed with either liberal use of ammunition or explosives.Use of explosives is slightly less punishing, as most enemies do not drop anything lootable.Research, base construction, gathering intel and research is quite intuitive with few quirks. It can be somewhat annoying having just starting checking out (scanning) a rumour, then having to fly to the other side of earth to do a mission, but that's part of the game.The game is mostly enjoyable and can become a decent addition to the XCOM / X-COM games, given proper mods or patches.Negatives:Insufficient quality assurance.a) Watching twitch streams and playing the final mission myself, the game may suddenly 'corrupt' in the last room, 		with visual artifacts and colors blooming and flickering. This bug makes it hard to concentrate on the (acid trip-looking) gameplay.b) The game may crash to desktop after killing the last required enemy on the final mission, in one instance causing a corrupt save.c) Overwatch shots may go through solid walls and hit.d) Melee attacks may occour through solid roofs or floors (vertical).e) Pull mechanics may go through multiple covers, visibly dragging the unfortunate soldier through.Constant nagging from Central, combined with loss of cameracontrol. This remains an issue even with the reduced v/o option.Constant delays after completing actions, e.g. heal a unit with a gremlin (drone) from far off, then watch as the gremlin slowly flies back to the operator. The loss of cameracontrol cannot be cancelled.Mods are great, but removing or adding mods can (or will) ruin your savegames. Considering mods can be withdrawn from the workshop, this can be an issue for ironman playthroughs.Accuracy. For some reason, standing in the tile next to a flanked muton gives less than a 100 % accuracy when using a shotgun.In-betweens:The player is limited to four classes, each consisting of skills divided into two subclasses. Stats like health, movement, aim, etc. are standardized and a soldier is simply given a class on promotion from rookie. Personalizing soldiers based on stats, e.g. making a high mobility assault/scout type soldier, is no longer an option. Personally, I found it giving to be able to select gear, classes and skills with stats and end results in the field in mind.The Psi-operative is nigh overpowered compared to the other classes.The concealment mechanic is interesting and allows for setting up ambushes or completing exfiltrationmissions almost without combat.Soldier panic can be chaotic. Soldiers can run to new cover and shoot or use items. This can lead to situations where the paniced soldier runs towards the main army of aliens and turns around and lobs a grenade toward an alien standing next to the rest of your soldiers. The result is no cover for your own guys, possible death and more panic, not to mention your paniced soldier possibly beeing exposed (thus dead). Drawing lines back to X-COM Apocalypse, simular actions could happen, as a paniced soldier would either freeze, start shooting at whatever was in front of him (including friendly fire) or run away from enemies. Personally, I find that a paniced soldier is too unpredictable in XCOM 2, as the friendly fire can be a bit over the top in a game where friendly fire is mainly a none-issue. It's a matter of taste.Turn limit. Most missions are limited by a max number of turns to complete the mission. This serves to give the player the feeling that the aliens at any minute may tumble down and create a full lockdown on the area, but in most cases, it makes little sense to activate the timer when the squad is concealed. For some reason, it's OK that it takes maybe 6 hours to fly to the mission, but somehow, you are limited by minutes from the minute your team hits the ground undetected.New mechanics have a tendensy to be stuffed down the player's gullet. Prime example is trying to kill a muton with a melee attack (specialty of the ranger), only to have said muton block and counterattack the ranger. I'm usually a fan of aliens beeing scary in itself, e.g. the popper, multiworm or brainsucker in Apocalypse, but I'm not a fan of counterattacks with no other possible counterplay than not ever using melee on said unit.Restart mission option if you fail the final mission, even with ironman activated. Why...?"
76561198073168284,Recommended,268500,32621579,Posted: 21 June,all,Fotivator,"I'm not going to give some groundbreaking review so i'm just going to give my short opinion which is what drove me to purchase the game. If you've ever played any turn based game (like civilization) this game is very close to that, with a substantial amount more of relating details (such as what cover your troops are using and what equipment they brought with them into the field.) to affect the end result of the battle. The damage and combat are very realistic (for a sci-fi era game). The story is good and you feel involved the longer the game goes on. This game is (from what i've been told) is much harder than xcom1 and has a substantial learning curve attached to it. But once you understand the games mechanics, you can easily pull 75-100 hours out of this game.Now for the cons, there are only two:1) The fact that the developers took co-op mods out of this game destroyed any chance this series had for any type of true longevity play. It's now a single-player experience and the ""multiplayer"" is buggy and seems pretty dead.2) The game (despite having a great story line) doesn't change after your first play through. So unlike Civ where you can win games in multiple ways, this has a linear story path. So take your time on your first play through and enjoy it, because once you've played the game all the way through to the end, you've seen all it has to offer. After that happens the game starts to become mundane with repetition in combat. Well, it did for me at least. I've also seen reviews on here with 500 hours played, so to each his own I guess.TLDR; It's a fantastic game with a fantastic combat system and story line. However after you've beaten it once, I don't really see a lot of replay value with this game."
