,Recommended,268500,33174893,Posted: 3 July,all,headache,"Thought that I might as well chip in my two cents, since I'm one vanilla campaign down and a third of a Long War 2 in.Many Steam positive reviews tell you to discredit the negative reviews in some strange attempt at creating an in-group with you, the reader. That's not fair to the consumer, though, and I'd prefer to tell you tolistento the negative reviews. If you aren't open to the idea of timed missions in a turn-based strategy, where you're looking at 8 turns to defuse a bomb, you may want to skip this title. Because there's a lot of that in vanilla. Long War 2 alleviates this a bit by extending timers to 10-24 turns most of the time, but then that is offset by other timers introduced by Long War 2, such as how long it'll take to infiltrate and exfiltrate a mission.I'd also say the ""recommended reading"" for this game would be at least watching a playthrough of XCOM: Enemy Unknown/Enemy Within if you're not interested in actually completing it on your own. Some of the elements may be more sci-fi B-movie than ""Jesus Christ, that's a giant naked mole rat on twelve lines of cocaine"", but the gameplay is very similar and knowing what each enemy can throw at you is second to none in keeping your guys alive. After all, Sun Tzu once said, ""It is said that if you know your enemies and know yourself, you will not be imperiled in a hundred battles.""So now you're thinking, ""Gee whiz, headache, you dashing individual, you. First you're saying I may outright not like the game if I don't like a certain mechanic, and now you're saying I need to play other games to fully understand it? What gives? Where's the good part?""Here's the good part.What you get with XCOM 2 is a highly modular, streamlined experience. Despite my eldritch-possessed laptop being easily half a decade old, I can tell through the 10-30 frames per second I'm getting that the controls are tight and the gameplay fluid. Classes have synergy in both vanilla and Long War 2, abilities feel potent, and our lord and savior Overwatch still has its use (though it's been relegated to more of a supportive role than an all-in role). Weapon modification feels purposeful and can be tailored to each individual role of your troops. Being able to pick the class your rookie gets gives you a sense of autonomy over what used to be a largely in-the-air affair.Oh right, I said modular, too.XCOM 2 has both Steam Workshop and Nexus support, meaning you can get a slew of mods for all your needs. Want a harder game? A Better Advent and Long War 2 are there for you. Want an easier game? There's stuff for that, too! Want to look like your soldiers walked straight out of Metal Gear Solid 5? Titanfall? Fallout: New Vegas? XCOM: Enemy Unknown? Gears of War? An unholy mixture of all five? You do you, Commander. There's also various tweaks and fixes available, such as the one that shows whether your move will put an enemy in range or flank them (Gotcha!). I'm running somethhing like ninety mods that range from giving me the sultry tones of Sergeant Johnson from Halo as a voice for my boots on the ground to entirely changing the strategic gameplay.If I were to rate things with numbers, I'd probably take into consideration the situational entertainment value of XCOM 2 weighed against its capable content and player-driven narrative. But I'm not good at numbers, so all you get is that.EDIT:Now I'm halfway through that Long War 2 playthrough, and I realized a lot of these reviews (including mine) mention, but do not describe or review, Long War 2. Since it's strategically a different game, I'd say it's worth its own mini-review. If you're not interested in Long War 2, you can skip this last bit.At six points in the base game, you are given a uniform upgrade to your most widely-used matériel. Either your weapons or your armor are upgraded, and while you can still choose to use previous tiers, there's no reason not to: you have an infinite amount of these new items at your disposal. Less-used items like grenades and specialty ammo still need to be produced randomly, but you often have the supplies necessary at your disposal.Long War 2 removes these gamey stratifications and forces you to face the music of logistics. Each gun, each set of armor, and each utility need to be produced individually (with the exception of starter gear), and you will often not have the supplies to equip all your soldiers with your best items. This means you often have to weigh the difficulty of the mission against the skill of your troops to determine who gets the new guns and who gets the old model.There’s also far more missions in Long War 2 – not just overall, but at a single time. This is managed by the infiltration system, which (flavor-wise) involves deploying your soldiers to a location where they observe enemy movements and wait for the ideal time to strike. This can take days on the strategic map (passed, as usual, by scanning) and is almost unavoidably necessary to avoid a complete squad wipe.With each deployed squad requiring the equipment and infiltration time to accomplish their mission, you can begin to see the appeal (or lack thereof) for Long War 2. There’s a lot of changes, and not all of them are explained thoroughly. For example, I spend about as much time on the deployment menu as I do on the mission.  You’ll need trial, error, and time to really get the feel for it, and if you can’t spend the hours and stay cool when things go up in flames, it may not be for you. However, if you’re looking for something more akin to a reversed Total War (i.e.: turn-based battles and real-time overworld) about a global insurgency, this is your mod."
