76561198014493471,Not Recommended,268500,31328288,Posted: 23 April,all,Vermillion_Hawk,"I can not in good faith recommend this game to anyone who claims to be a fan of strategy games or X-COM as a series. After a successful campaign played, and several others started and promptly aborted, I find myself looking back on my time with this game as being utterly wasted and unrewarding. Here's why.If you are a fan of strategy games, like myself, and know nothing of the X-COM series, you're better off either getting the original, Xenonauts or the 2012 remake that this game is a sequel of. The former two actually reward tactics and strategy, while the latter is at least fun, despite its tactical shallowness. This game features none of the fun of its predecessor. Both games claim to be in the ""hardcore"" spectrum of games, and while games like the original 1994 game earn that moniker by presenting the player with difficult, but ultimately winnable scenarios that have multiple solutions based on player skill, this game earns it by merely presenting the player with a series of weighted dice rolls.XCOM 2 loves its dice, and this becomes apparent right from the beginning of a campaign. Skipping the tutorial (a multi-hour affair valuable only to someone who has never touched a strategy game before in their life), the intro campaign mission on anything but normal difficulty will rapidly introduce you to XCOM 2's idea of difficulty. Your soldiers, at their basic state, will hover at a66%chance to hit any enemy with aflanking advantage- while your enemies don't have better chances, provided your soldiers are positioned adequately, they are more than equipped to mitigate their own failings - even basic enemy patrols at the beginning of the game will often include an officer enemy who, provided the AI doesn't make a stupid decision (another dice roll), can mark one of your soldiers, making them much more likely to take a hit from any enemy, and shoot, all in the same turn. If you don't find yourself against one of these officers, you might find yourself up against a Sectoid, whose cover-ignoring psionics can make your soldiers panic, waste a turn and reposition to an often-disadvantageous position where they'll likely be flanked and killed with little effort from your foes.The player, conversely, is presented with few tools to mitigate the abhorrent effects of the game's RNG - when 66% is the best you can expect on a flanking shot from even a middling range, the only reliable tools at your disposal are grenades and melee, and the latter has the unfortunate yet obvious side-effect of forcing your units into close quarters, making it suitable only as a finishing touch to an engagement. An enemy introduced fairly early into the meat of a campaign, as well, can, without prior warning or indication, block even the most veteran Ranger's blade and deliver a counterattack, usually resulting in the death of your unit, so melee is hardly a reliable friend in tactically adverse situations. Reliable damage-dealing abilities and player-controlled psionics are also options, but only at a point in the campaign where a player has already dealt with the worst that XCOM 2 has to offer.And worst it is. The first 10 or so missions of any campaign are guaranteed to be the most brutal on offer of any that you will deal with over the course of the game. Simulating scarcity by giving the player an under-equipped force is one thing, but how the player is expected to deal with it is ridiculous. Off the battlefield, on the world map layer of the game, the player is expected to amass resources, develop better equipment and try to foil ADVENT (the alien antagonists) and their Avatar Project, a constantly ticking clock at the top of your screen that is introduced within the first few missions. The problem with all this is that, like everything else in the game, your progress will largely be decided by dice rolls. ""Investigation sites"" pop up on the world map, and the player can spend in-game days following these leads for a variety of resources and rewards. These are entirely random, and the first few sites a player can access can determine the fate of an entire campaign, thanks to ADVENT ramping up their forces far faster than your own if things play out poorly. Getting an incredibly valuable engineer as your first site can make all the difference in whether or not you can take 5 or 6 soldiers into combat instead of the base 4, or if your units will be expected to fight Vipers, Faceless or Mutons with conventional weapons or Railguns. Getting supplies (the game's currency) or recruits as your first few sites, on the other hand, can mean being dangerously underequipped for the next several missions, resulting in inevitable casualties, and the casualties are indeed inevitable. Unlike in its immediate predecessor, where unit damage resulted in a brief convalescing period for unarmoured units or MECs, units that take a single hit in combat might be put out of action for close to an entire in-game month; an almost-unacceptable loss when a campaign only spans maybe 6 or 7 months. Mitigating this requires devoting engineers, personnel vital to construction and therefore progress, to medic duty, something that probably should have been relegated to scientists, who have comparatively little else to do, and only one building to supervise compared to the 4 or so vital buildingsrequiringthe attention of an engineer. The game, therefore, punishes you for even trying to mitigate the effects of a combat RNG failure by stalling your progress, either through bad design or through malicious intent.The illusion of choice on the strategic layer is, therefore, just that - an illusion. A player can decide to rush down certain avenues (psionics vs. weapons vs. armor vs. squad buffs, for example), and the lacklustre DLCs add additional paths to prioritize, but any of these options have the same result on the battlefield; you'll either stomp your foes or be stomped. There is no middle ground in XCOM 2, thanks to the sheer cruelty of its dice rolls. Until one researches the top tier of armor and weapons, or obtain fully kitted-out psionic soldiers, one can only plan for the eventuality of losing a veteran soldier, which can happen in the short and brutal span of a single enemy turn, if the dice will it so.The campaign itself is predictable - relatively open-ended campaign missions only serve to bracket the purpose-built campaign ""levels"", much like its predecessor, and the story doesn't go in any particularly interesting directions. The characters aren't anything special, but neither were they in the first game, and characterization is only a bonus at best in a strategy game, so no points are lost on this. For all its focus on the ""story"", however, the campaign manages to end on a definitively lacklustre and humdrum final mission, something which almost every X-COM clone or remake has had an issue with. Gone are the days of taking the fight to the aliens, using their own technology to make a spacefaring vessel and bombing their base on Mars to kingdom come (the original game's ending) - this game's final mission has none of that intensity, and even has the gall to end on a cliffhanger, despite plans on forthcoming expansions or DLCs being apparently relegated to third party development in the form of the Long War team.That I've been motivated to write so many words on this game should speak to my devotion to the series and to strategy gaming in general. So few games with the production values and expertise put into XCOM 2 come out in the genre that it would be tempting to give it a pass purely on that basis. However, a focus on brutal RNG in place of difficulty through good design prove to be crippling flaws to what should otherwise be a fantastic game, to say nothing of further development on it being apparently outsourced.Final score: 4/10, with prejudice. Not worth full price by any means, and certainly not worth an extended period of time."
