76561198001958882,Recommended,268500,23505202,"Posted: 11 June, 2016",all,Genocider,"XCOM 2 is definitely a game with a few issues, mainly in the performance department. That said Firaxis have been supporting the game and patching it to solve issues many have had. I can run the game fairly decently, and enjoy my time with it.It's also a turn based game, and while that's no excuse, a lower FPS than 60 is still playable here. The gameplay itself is a step up from it's predecessor, with you taking on the role of Guerillas rather than Soldiers. It's an interesting take on the franchise as you'll be the one making the decisions on when to attack and ambush rather than the other way around.In the first game you'd overwatch crawl your way to victory, trying to avoid activating pods in unfortunate scenarios. With Enemy Within, meld was an incentive to do more than just crawl across the map, and it worked fairly well. XCOM 2 expanded on that idea with a good chunk of missions having a timer where you'll fail the mission if you don't complete it in time. It's a bit contrived but gets the job done, however to make up for this you start most of these timed missions in concealment allowing you to pick when to engage and blow your cover.It's not a stealth game, I still have yet to complete a single mission without 'alerting' the aliens, however the stealth system does allow you to do something you had a harder time doing in the first game, ambush the enemy and pick when to engage.The gameplay itself has a lot of mods in the works, and is much easier to mod than the first game. Already there are plenty of mods that add new enemies, soldier customizations, voice lines, and map parcels (Maps in XCOM 2 are randomly generated so they get less static than the ones in the first game). There's nothing on the level of Long War for Xcom 1 yet, but the possibility is there and if the community makes the effort to create something like that, I'm sure it can be done.Is XCOM 2 a worthy successor to the first game? I'd say so. Is it a replacement for the first game? Well, the first game with no expansions I'd definitely say so. However is it a replacement for Enemy Within? No, I'd suggest anyone who's yet to try XCOM try out Enemy Within first, however I do think XCOM 2 is simply better than Enemy Within (Optimization aside).I'd put it like this, Long War for XCOM 1 has more depth than XCOM 2, however XCOM 2 is far superior to Enemy Within and Enemy Unknown. I'd also argue that XCOM 2 is an easier game on the harder difficulties, however mods already exist that can tweak the game to be harder or easier to whiatever suits you.Whether it's worth the price of admission is up to you, but with Steam refunds being a thing I'd certainly suggest trying it and giving it a shot, especially if you're a fan of the first game. If strategy games with a bit of chance are your thing, then XCOM 2 and it's tense engagements will certainly be for you.Edit: I've read a few negative reviews and most focus on the timed missions and Strategic side of the game. Here's the thing, the timers prevent you from simply crawling up the map without taking many calculated risks. If you dislike the timers you can edit them in LTX files or download mods from the workshop that elongate or remove them.As for the Strategy side, many were complaining that they didn't have enough time to do everything available there before getting into a mission. That's the point, with Advent controlling the world you'll have to make decisions about where you dedicate your resources. You'll usually be able to get one of the 'resource blips' before a mission, but not all of them. It's about choosing which one you think is more important to you, going for it, and then doing the mission.What's nice about XCOM 2 is that failing a mission or skipping a mission isn't a death sentence like it was in the first game. Yes on higher difficulties missing early missions can be terrible, however there are ways to get around this. Missions simply aren't as impactful, they're still important...But you have ways of getting around the cost of failure.You may have failed a mission and lost a Veteran soldier, but you now have ways of acquiring new soldiers for resources you have. Managing your resources is an important part of the strategic side as I mentioned, and they're much more important in XCOM 2 than the first game. Not only can you get new soldiers but you can get Scientists and Engineers as well, though it's important to remember you'd miss out on other things such as making new contacts, or getting some weapon upgrades. You can even spend resources to rush some research or building if that's what you'd like to try doing.The types of strategies you can emply thanks to these extra systems are just another bit of depth outside the Tactical game. So yes you won't be able to get everything available on the world map, you'll have to pick and choose. The thing is, you have much more to do resource wise, and many more decisions to make that add depth to the game.Also important not to forget, thanks to how easy it is to modify the game and how open the devs have been with this, you can change things such as timers or how long collecting resources takes yourself or by looking around on the workshop. Hope this helps clear a few things up and spread some light on a few issues I've seen people have."
