,Not Recommended,268500,21124636,"Posted: 11 February, 2016",all,himmatsj,"XCOM 2 is largely a refinement of and an advancement on XCOM: Enemy Unknown. It honestly doesn't feel like a full sequel. Feels like XCOM: Enemy Unknown 1.5. But that's not really a bad thing. As mentioned, many things have been refined and streamlined, and there have been a host of new additions that do mix things up to a certain degree. Though yes, at the same time, I must say I am a tad disappointed that things aren't more different.So, long story short, if you like XCOM: EU you will most probably like XCOM 2 as well. The campaign length for a first run is around 40-50 hours.Now, the game has some glaring issues. One is optimization. I honestly do not find the graphics to be anything stellar (they don't seem that different from in XCOM EU), but even on the lowest settings I am getting absolutely terrible performance.Another is from time to time, the game can bug out. I hacked a Sectapod successfully, yet somehow it remains out of my control and kills my troops on the next turn. Then there was once a muton who was actually on the roof, but the graphics made it look like it was at the bottom of the roof. And once my scanning went to -3 days (it just bugged out).Gameplay wise, too many enemies are just bullet sponges in the mid-to-late game.Now that I am right at the end of the final mission, I can say that this game suffers the same two issues from XCOM EU.1) The mid-to-late game is relatively much, much easier than the fiendishly difficult early game.2) There is no ""middle ground"" difficulty setting between Veteran (a tad too easy) and Commander (a tad too difficult)This game is a net recommendation actually but I leave a thumbs down until Firaxis can fix the optimization issues at least."
