76561198018586514,Not Recommended,268500,24844069,"Posted: 12 August, 2016",all,PoorYorick,"I will be brutally honest about my review here: I am not being objective. This is pure oppinion and if you enjoy the game it is completely and utterly up to you.So, did I like it?No, I hated it fully and completely. The game has very clear goals and none of them are admirable or interesting.While XCom: Enemy Unknown had issues, two things that I loved about it were the scope and the story. It felt like the desperate attempt of an unsuspecting planet to fight against a highly superior invader.That feeling is gone. The game tries to go for a ""fight the POWA!"" feel, but it utterly fails on a mechanical level. Missions are always about attacking and routing or anihilating the enemy. Enemies (like before) only activate once spoted, so you never feel like a covert ops team. In fact, your soldiers become so strong during the game, I hardly ever had one seriously hurt. By adding more content, the developers overlooked the dreadded powercreep.Now for the second titanic issue: The story*Spoilers*While XCom: Enemy Unknown went with a very event and action driven narrative that was mostly told through the memos and Ufopedia entries, it allowed the player a very good feel of what the enemy was up to and made it clear that XCom, while necessary was a very shady organization. You got black money from a shady council, constantly lauched military actions in neutral airspace and basically confiscated alien technology right from the soil of sovereign nations. Your actions were not black and white.XCom 2 forgoes these ideas and makes it obvious: Aliens EVUL, rebels GOOD, you HERO!The narrative is mostly character driven, following 4 people who handle everything (scientists and engineers only support, you never get the feeling that there is a whole legion of workers behind any breakthrough). Sadly, the characters are neither very deep nor very interesting. Due to the fact that rebels need constant rescue from you (the new terror missions are attacks on rebel bases), they come off as completely ineffectual and kinda sad. Your fellow freedom fighters have the same AI as civilians in the first installment and never take a shot or fight back.Finally, there are the aliens... The strange, unsettling enemy of mankind that has unified dozen of species and attacked you without provocation for no reason have basically become Dr. Robotnik from Sonic. Their motives are outright stated at the halfway point and their evilness is underlined with Auschwitz-imagery and their personal Steven Jobs - like spokesman. At some point they ""want to harvest the entire genetic material of the world"" by putting people into meat grinding factories. The final cutscene features the Commander himself in Psy-battle with the alien leaders. Yes, it has become that simple and dumb. It ends with a hint at what I assume will be the next installment. Anyways, I really didn't enjoy this game. Sorry, hope you do"
