76561198012756377,Not Recommended,268500,22308436,"Posted: 8 April, 2016",all,propy05,"This game probably has a lot of potential, but it's too broken to know for sure.  Many times I would have a soldier aim at one enemy, but then shoot at another one that I didn't intend because of some glitch.  The camera has an odd tendency to slowly drift on its own when you're planning a movement or aiming a grenade which results in leaving your soldier in the open or missing a toss.  Whenever an NCP in the game talks to you on the radio, you're not able to take any action, and there is ALOT of radio chatter, which is usually reminding you of mission objectives that you already know or telling you about the mission timer of which you're already well aware.  There is an option that makes it seem like you can reduce this needless dialogue, but it has no noticeable effect, making missions last much longer than they need to and adding frustration to the already broken system.  It's disappointing to have the experience ruined by game glitches, bugs, and wasted time, and until they fix these problems, I cannot recommend playing this game.  Was very excited for XCOM 2, but ultimately very disappointed and frustrated."
,Not Recommended,268500,24924460,"Posted: 14 August, 2016",all,ZhuGeLiang,"I would recommend this game, and for people who truly enjoy strategy games, science fiction, strategy, and cheesy storylines, I would still recommend it - but for numerous reasons, to the general rpg and strategy player, I simply can't provide my recommendation of XCOM2. Here's why.First of all, the game is incredibly demanding on PC resources - so much so that even with a near top-of-the-line air-cooled rig, I run it on low settings. It is buggy and crashes occasionally. There are frame drops and hiccups. I had issues with the cinematics when it was first installed - sound would play out of sync, and sometimes the cinematics wouldn't show at all.Secondly, it is overpriced for what you get. The DLCs add very little to the game, and the rewards from completing them are quite hefty from a resource-cost standpoint. Even if you forego all of the DLC, on Commander+ difficulties you will find yourself grinding missions simply to get more resources before the final assault. Throw in the DLC rewards, and you will very quickly realize just how much of a grind XCOM2 can be.Third, there are no *real* choices in XCOM2. When you have access to three guerrilla operations, you are merely choosing between the best reward in most cases (which is typically fairly obvious.) Outside of that, your only choices will be whether or not to spend intel to buy a weapon upgrade on the black market, or spend resources on your ranger shotguns instead of sharpshooter sniper rifles. Missions are completely linear, and some missions are literally impossible to complete thanks to cheating AI and random spawn locations. (One time I spawned on a map with four alien groups that triggered simultaneously the following turn, even if I didn't move.)There are no alternate endings besides success and failure. Missions do not change much even on new playthroughs - you will meet new aliens at approximately the same times and in the same order. There are only three or four game-progress missions that *require* completion. The rest are time wasters and provide a slow trickle of resources...which are the only real impediment to your progress. Player skill and good decision making will not impact your completion speed much - only the random rolls for whether or not you get downed UFO missions will influence that.It becomes painfully obvious eventually - 95% of the missions are simply obstacles to your progress within the game, and barely feel like they *are* the game. They're more like a house fly that won't stop landing on your arm. Your actual success or failure depends not on completing these missions, but rather on whether or not you have the resources to obtain region contacts to reach the missions you *need* to progress. This lack of importance makes 95% of the game - the mass of meaningless missions - feel like the filler on a one-hit-wonder music album.If I were to rate XCOM2, I'd give it a 6/10. It's not a terrible game by any means, and I know a lot of work went into it, but it seems like they never finished it. Maybe they expected the mod community to do the work for them...maybe they figured they'd make their money back and some more, and that'd be enough. But the lack of RPG-type customizeability on soldiers, the apparent meaninglessness of most missions, and the on-rails story really ruins what would otherwise be a solid turn-based strategy game."
76561197994903522,Not Recommended,268500,21280614,"Posted: 17 February, 2016",all,Germanico,"This brief review comes from an old time veteran of UFO games going all the way back to the 90s. Being a great fan of the relaunched Xcom the second installment was an autobuy. And I am very confident they will eventually patch it to where it should be, but...Even on easiest setting some of the missions are extremely hard - mainly due to the RNG gameplay mechanics built into the core mechanics: I've had to reload for literally 2 evenings to finish one of the missions because of flaws in my team that I simply could not have prevented as a player. And that comes from a ironman player of Xcom 1. I have no qualms with being punished for stupid gameplay - in Xcom2 I am constantly reloading simply because stuff happens that I have absolutely no control over.The alien opponents seemingly use their maximum movement range and still melee attack - or they have insane range. And why Aliens get an out of turn movement phase when they are surprised by my team beats me. Result as so often is that they can essentially flank the hell out of me without my team even being able to reposition.The timers are extremely tight and often enough I had to restart missions all the way from the beginning simply because I had that one turn missing to finish the extraction. I even had to leave folks behind due to the constantly reapearing aliens - without my guys having a fair chance to fight their way out. No one left behind? Not in Xcom2.And don't get me even started on the hit/cover percentages... Let's say it this way: they really need some love.Story and core combat of the game are great and absolutely addicting. It's just not really polished for the player yet. But I am sure it will happen over time and then my hesitant ""NO"" will become an overwhelming ""YES""... until then: you either have to be a lucky star OR masochistic. Or both..."
