,Recommended,268500,35500918,Posted: 5 October,all,Grizzy,"XCOM 2 is a turn-based tactical strategy game where every decision has lasting consequences -- good or bad.Introduction:Firstly, you are the ""commander"" of XCOM, a once globally funded military organisation tasked with one job: to keep aliens from invading Earth. But after almost 20 years having passed XCOM have failed, and alien overlords, referred to as ""Advent"", occupy planet Earth.As a result of this, XCOM was forced to go off the radar to avoid certain doom, and now operates as a resistance force, attempting to maliciously sabotage alien activity, blacksites and research labs whilst striving to spread ""dissident propaganda"" to help humanity open their eyes to the atrocities of Advent, all from their new mobile base, ""The Avenger"".Gameplay:XCOM is highly luck based. Things will go wrong. Sometimes you will fail miserably; sometimes you won't. The first step to playing XCOM is accepting that things will not always go your way, you will miss 99% chances to hit, you will be outmatched, and you will lose many soldiers along the way, especially on higher difficulties and in the early game.As you progress, however, you will research better weaponry, armour, abilities for soldiers to use weapon attachments, etc. This combined with making use of the new concealment mode will give opportunities for powerful ambushes.Customisation:The customisation options are decent with a good amount of items to wear and customise but lacks real depth, being able to choose from very few faces and haircuts.The modding scene more than makes up for this though, with a rather extensive wardrobe and customisation options available to download, along with some more appealing gameplay overhauls to compliment it.Robustness:Not much to add here other than that I've personally never had any issues with how the game runs or experienced a single crash in all my hours of gameplay.Art:The art and aesthetics of XCOM 2 are absolutely beautiful. It perfectly captures and envisions how Earth might look after 20 years of alien colonisation. Everything from the modern, vibrant and clean look of the Advent city centres to the abandoned towns, which feel like they were once bustling cities that people actually lived in, now lie in complete ruins. This combined with the superb map generation, beautiful animations and character astetics make it an absolutely georgous game.Conclusion:XCOM 2 is not only a fantastic game, but a fantastic sequel. It improves on almost every aspect from its predecessor and is an absolute must buy. Although it becomes particularly easy towards the end game, it is still incredibly satisfying to play and ultimately about out-thinking your enemy. If you do not own XCOM 2, I strongly recommend purchasing it, even at full price.9/10Superb."
