76561198034238053,Recommended,268500,25991786,"Posted: 11 October, 2016",all,Justy,"The overall experience is solid - but.I understand it's not easy to live up to the kind of success the 2012 XCOM inarguably was, but there is a way it shouldn't be done, and that is making a major part of the sequel consist of a slightly different retelling of the original. It's not that I mind the retcon, and the dystopian society certainly has an appeal, and XCOM2 is nowhere near the lazy reskin that was the 1995 TFTD.Still, once the initial freedom fighting and customization high tapers off, you start to realize the storyline is seriously underwhelming, and the way the game has you running around the clock both in the tactical mode and on the geoscape mostly serves to distract you from how barebones everything is compared to EU+EW.It's another step down in complexity compared to the originals (which weren't overly complex to begin with, despite what many people claim), and this time it hits harder. There's a line between streamlining and truncating. I believe XCOM 2 has crossed it, and not even the constant ticking of the clock can conceal the fact. Sure, you can still choose a plethora of approaches in the tactical mode (mostly thanks to the skill trees, this time bordering on magic even more heavily), but other than that the game is reduced to something akin Pac-man. Unfortunately, the DLCs that could have been the game's saving grace are also very hit-or-miss, trending on the miss with the exception of Shen's Last Gift. Comparing any of them to EW is just out of the question.I enjoyed the game a great deal, so I can't but recommend it, and I look forward to any major DLCs that might expand the gameplay further, but as it is now it just isn't worth it for the full price."
