,Recommended,268500,21002050,"Posted: 6 February, 2016",all,Permanent Marker,"Let me start by saying XCOM 2 is a triumph. XCOM EU and EW paid homage to UFO Defence's difficulty and fear factor by making sure the game was truly difficult, but in a mostly rewarding way. In some ways they compromised on those principles - having your best squad wiped a few weeks in and losing a critical mission was basically game over, so half the time losses felt frustrating rather than just punishing and reinvigorating. In my first XCOM 2 run, that I consider to have gone fairly well, I've lost upwards of 10 soldiers in a few months, and I failed my first attempt at a blacksite, but I can tell I'm that I'm not doomed. Notably, in EU, there were a lot of safety net abilities like Run and Gun, Rockets and various Sniper abilities like Double Tap though that made the game at times laughably easy - so long as you had restraint.XCOM 2's biggest change to the formula, outside of the total revamp of the strategic layer,  is the fact that there are almost no safety nets in the early game. Rockets are gone, replaced with grenade launchers, which while incredibly useful, cannot wipe out a pod of enemies in one shot every mission.  The new Ranger class, which is basically like the old Assault, doesn't get Run and Gun until midway through the ability tree. The sword they get has effectively enormous range, but can't be relied upon to singlehandedly kill enemies unless you get bladesman at corporal rank, which loses you an extremely useful concealment abiility.  Specialists are about as underwhelming as supports were early on, but get just as deadly in later ranks, while Sharp Shooters are heavily situational due to the fact that a lot of missions are timed, but can now do some very interesting stunts like fire off pistols a couple times a round at different targets, or chain sniper rifle shots together if each one is a kill. The fact the aliens are now more specialised, and their gimmicks are more frightening (e.g, the basic sectoid gets the mind control ability in the first few months)  means that without safety nets, they're far more fearsome and worth being worried about. This makes the game more difficult obviously, but also more enjoyable in the long run once you know how to handle each type of enemy - Sectoids are easily killed by swords, Stunlancers either need to die ASAP or you need a flashbang/overwatch to shut them down from charging. The Faceless, meanwhile, needs to be spotted well in advance of triggering it, because it can attack on activation.  The variation in alien types and the threat they present means that XCOM 2 encourages a lot more tactical, outside the box thinking.The visuals in this game are incredible. The unit design for the aliens and advent hybrids is superb, and really adds to the intimidation when they're breathing down your neck. The environmental design is also great - the procedural generation is by no means a half baked gimmick and makes every area look interesting and refreshing.  There are cobbled together outposts, futuristic cities, slums, surreal alien bases and facilities.  Customisation is top notch - there is as a lot of freedom and oppurtunity for making your own narrative in your head, and in general things that make your troops more memorable, like random extra abilities, the memorial/bar and personnel areas you can view all add to the attachment you get to them.I want to quickly mention the multiplayer. This is a mixed bag - the extremely points heavy advent robot units are extremely hard to kill and can one-shot most targets. The Sectopod, ludicrously, can even fire twice, doing 10-11 damage each time.  The costs on units are very weird, as is some of the internal balance. Advent Troopers at 200 points have 3 health and a mag rifle, but for 400 points you get an Officer with 12 health, better stats, a frag grenade and the ability to mark targets. Since matches total about 7500+ points, you can easily fit these guys in.  There is an issue with stuttering as well which I'll touch upon in a moment.In terms of technical quality, you can tell that the developers didn't put their effort towards making a game that was very free of bugs, or that ran extremely well. The game is stable - the amount of disruptive bugs that will ruin your experience or progress is very, very minimal and rare it seems. The problems arise with the fact that XCOM 2 just simply doesn't run as well as it should on high end PCs- there are frequent FPS drops in missions unless you turn some settings down.  This obvously doesn't matter that much, since the game is turn based, but it is irritating. Perhaps the most annoying bug is the fact that the game occassionally takes a few seconds to register a buff/debuff/critical effect, or upwards of 10-20 seconds to end a turn in multiplayer and pass control to the other player. This is something that is bound to be fixed eventually though.I whole-heartedly reccomend XCOM 2 to anyone who was a fan of XCOM EU, and would also say that anyone who has an interest in a challenging and interesting game but has not tried the games before this one should give it a go at least."
76561197997448611,Recommended,268500,20996893,"Posted: 6 February, 2016",all,Sunny,this is the proof you do not have to reinvent a great game. Just update the setting and the gfx. voila!
,Recommended,268500,21018463,"Posted: 6 February, 2016",all,/:\,"70% rating? Come on, this game is fantastic. I've played 10 hours of this game so far, and I haven't enjoyed a game so much in this way since, well, XCOM EU.Let me explain what I mean: This game is terrifying. Every single mission is down to the wire. Every mission can and will go wrong. And the whole time, I'm sitting there thinking, ""Don't miss don't miss don't miss Oh ****""And that's great. Seriously. That's awesome, and that's where XCOM shines. Risk/reward is a huge part of what makes the experience as satisfying or compelling as it is.So if someone complains that the game is too hard, they're missing the point. I mean, jeez guys. We're liberating the human race from technologically superior aliens. Why did you expect it to be easy?Anyways, half the fun of XCOM is when everything goes to hell and yet, somehow, you scrape together a victory.Disclaimer: this game is harder than EU. Yeah, seriously. And so if you're considering getting this game, don't expect it to be a walk in the park. It's war. But it's incredible."
