,Recommended,268500,20969489,"Posted: 5 February, 2016",all,Enthusiastically Wrong,"tl;dr If you're a fan of XCOM or tactical strategy games, you'll probably enjoy this. The difficulty is steep but for those who like hard games this may be part of the appeal. Performance concerns addressed below(zero spoilers) -For the record my rig is running a Radeon 380 GPU and FX6300 CPU, so nothing too fancy. Upper mid level at best. Now then...Little more in depth(NO SPOILERS):XCOM 2 goes the opposite direction of the first game in terms of plot. Rather than defending the Earth or, as Sid Meier put it, ""playing not to lose"", XCOM 2 puts you in the role of the resistance fighters after the aliens won 20 years prior. Some old characters return, with a cast of new ones as well, and the roster of enemies to kill has increased by quite a bit.Graphically the game looks pretty great. I had lag when I first booted up at the main menu but it was because the game defaulted to maxed out settings. Although my GPU isn't at the very top of the line, it is now running the game quite splendidly with all of the settings maxed except Anti-Aliasing. For some reason that's the only setting that seems to be giving my rig trouble. But it still looks pretty good with that turned down.Sound-wise, it's pretty standard fare. Dramatic music when the xenos spot you, triumphant orchestras when outfitting your squad. It does its work, sounds high quality, and is pleasant to hear but isn't spectacular. But not every studio can afford to hire Jeremy Soule.Performance(CPU) could be better. Considering this is day 1 of release I'm not surprised that the optimization is what it is. Loading screens sometimes lag, turns take maybe a second or two longer than you feel that they should, but overall it's not dreadful. I haven't had any freezing in game at all. Compared to some releases, XCOM 2 feels pretty smooth. My old FX6300 doesn't have any trouble with it, and that's a lower-mid AMD chip.Gameplay is what you would expect from XCOM. Fans of the last game will be able to pretty much jump right into the action. Start off with rookies and no special equipment, promote them as they gain experience and skills, cry when your favorite soldier gets killed by a rogue laser... good stuff. The chance to hit with each attack is percentile based, so bare that in mind. Some players may not enjoy that aspect. Difficulty can be adjusted however so if the game feels too hardcore you may still find a level you enjoy.Graphics - 9/10Sound - 8.5/10Gameplay - 9/10"
