76561198014702049,Not Recommended,268500,29056217,Posted: 6 January,all,Lord Tommy,"Pretty tired of an 81% chance to hit actually being a 0% chance to hit.I have 175 hours into XCOM Enemy Unknown/Within.  I got a lot of play out of that one.  And I preordered the big special edition of this expecting that this one would surpass that.Well, it didn't.  I finished my first playthrough of the game in about 24 hours and it was very frustrating.  This was before any of the content packs went live (as they were not at launch when I got the game).After seeing all the DLC had been released I loaded it up again eager to try out the new stuff.  But the new stuff, it really isn't that interesting at all.  With Enemy Within there were huge additions to the game.  Mechanized soldiers or bio enhanced ones added new depth to your strategies.The ones for X2 here mostly added aesthetics, a few interesting but overall useless weapons, and robot soldiers, which is just a retread of the exact same robot soldiers from XCOM  Enemy Within.Here I sit at about 59 hours in a love hate relationship with this game, I actually want to play it again but then I remember all the frustrating things about it.One of the things XCOM2 does is have more urgent missions, which is fun in a way.  You can't overwatch creep through maps, you have to move quickly and you have to take risks.  Unfortunately those risks often end in really bad results.This is a puzzle game.  The puzzle is loading multiple times to get the correct execution so you don't lose any one of your soldiers.  I want to write them off, I really do, but I can't.  For one, I get attached to them since I can custom make my own roster, which is neat.  Jack Bauer, Bear Grylls, Duke Nukem, Lara Croft, it's a dream team.But it takes so much to level guys up.  And they only advance on getting kills, not participating in a mission.  Support Units, guys with drones that are meant to buff and heal the party, they can't advance if they aren't killing aliens.  Doesn't matter how many missions they run, how many lives they save, if they don't get their kill quota they stay useless.So it takes so long to level up your squad, which means when you lose a guy, it hurts, it hurts a lot.  So you don't want to lose anyone, because there's so many things that put pressure on in the game.  In both playthroughs I could never get the Avatar Countdown to drop below 2 empty squares and ultimately fell apart in my second one.Losing good troops means losing the ability to mitigate the countdown.  And wounding times are so long.  Even when I try to bring along a couple of rookies to make sure I'm padding out my advancement, it's a battle with luck, since they need kills to advance.Some fights keeping a guy alive is all but impossible.  It's a puzzle game.  You keep reloading until you find the right combination of moves and attacks that keeps your squad alive.  And it doesn't help that the game pregens random numbers, meaning you will see the exact same result every time.  Which I find odd there was no option to change the random seed which iirc was added in Xcom (also exists in Civ 5 another Firaxis game).And I wish the devs addressed that, the need to constantly reload, because you have to keep your good guys alive, you can't lose them.  You can't run the end game with a field of rookies and survive without constant reloading.  And the load times are soooo loooonnng.After almost 60 hours, I'm done.  The new content just isn't enough to keep me playing, it's a waste of money.I've been gaming since my dad bought my fam a Commodore 64 in the mid 80's, so maybe I'm just too old.  The kids these days play their Dark Souls and talk about how awesome it is to die all the time and never make it past level 2.I like a challenge, but I don't like frustration.  And there's a fine line.  And I'm going to get a whole bunch of thumbs down because it isn't about whether a review is 'helpful' here, it's about whether or not you agree with someone's opinion.  And old gaming codgers like me are in the minority these days."
