,Recommended,268500,29602651,Posted: 31 January,all,Dead Master,"Alright, so I've played through this once completely, and here's what I've seen.Base rating: 9/10 easily. AAA strategy games work, just one at a time.Setting: You lost your campaign in XCOM: Enemy Unknown about two weeks in. The Aliens kidnap you and store you in a stasis suit, running war simulations that the Aliens used to command their own forces to conquer Earth, forming the ADVENT coalition with all nations in exchange for controlling everything. Using gene therapy clinics as a facade, they begin human experiments with a mysterious purpose. After a costly breakout from a secure site, you are rescued by your Central Officer and a few other recruits, who survived the invasion and has managed to build up a small resistance force, based in a mobile base made out of a repurposed alien supply ship, accompanied by a defector scientist and Dr. Shen's daughter, who explains that her father gave his life to build this ship before he disappeared. With this, the controls are handed to you, and you must take back Earth from the ADVENT coalition and stop the mysterious AVATAR project, whose exact location is unknown by undertaking guerilla ops, hacking data stores, rescuing rebel VIPs and capturing hostile ones, make contact with resistance cells around the world, and take on mysterious blacksites to destroy progress on the AVATAR project. The council speaker returns as a informant seated in the higher-ups of ADVENT, sending out secure supply drops to help the resistance.Opinion: Yes, this game is hard. But it's also random. I hear your cries of ""that's not fair!"" ""What's the point of the strategy part of it then?"" But fear not. The strategy is in slowing down the progress enough for the numbers to tip back in your favour, then release all that pent-up frustration on the ADVENT forces ten times over. I got to 11 out of 12 blocks on the AVATAR project before starting a mass destruction of blacksites across my contacted regions. This is not recommended as I think I might've cut it a little too close. Anyways, after that peak in the early to midgame, the game becomes significantly easier, if less interesting.Environment and level/world design: 9/10The geoscape returns from XCOM: EU, but the regions are divided a bit differently. Each main region is covered by a huge ADVNET state called ""New (original region name)"". There remains the six continent bonuses, and the mission icons sometime look a bit repetitive.The Avenger (Your mobile base) is well designed and thought-out in its design. There a about 12 areas to construct various facilities onboard, and clearing the debris from these areas gives you some supplies (currency).The mission levels are well designed, both logisitcally and aesthetically, but may become repetitive in the late game, aside from the main story missions (Which normally have a custom map).Mechanics: 10/10The scientist-engineeer system returns from XCOM: EU, but engineers are staffed in most facilities constructed in the 12 or so excavateable areas on the Avenger, or clear out debris themselves. Scientists directly reduce research time, and can be staffed in a laboratory (constructed facility) to increase their effect.The soldier system is changed. Instead of Assault, Heavy, Support, Sinper, MEC suits and Psionics; you have Ranger, Grenadier, Specialist, Sharpshooter, SPARK and Psi ops. They fill the same effective roles respectively, but most have their abilities altered drastically. Ranger can use shotguns, but has a sword as their secondary weapon. It's unusually effective. Grenadier is more focused on Armouring up and shredding armour of enemies than rockets. Specialists are the biggest change. Instead of a medkit by default, they come with a flying robot droid that can be used offensively or for healing. The sharpshooter isn't really changed that much, but Squadsight is the deafauly ability instead of snapshot. They have a pistol ability tree (their secondary weapon) or a Sinping tree. SPARK units are, like the MEC suits in the Enemy Within DLC, a bonus class. As part of Shen's last Gift DLC, they appear in a mission that's way too hard to take on at first. Equipped with a heavy weapon and a rokcet launcher, they are meant to be a tanky class in a game about stealth. Pretty useless, right? Wrong. They are a crutch member that just peters out at the endgame. Psi ops are handled very differently, as a seperate class selected only from rookies. Instead of an Ability tree, they train by spending time in the psionics facility, training a variety of abilities which you choose one out of three each time they train. By this method, you could field a late game psi op without him ever having spent a day in the field.AVATAR project: So I've mentioned this a few times in the review. The AVATAR project is an unknown project that several references are made to in the intercepted alien chatter. After discovering the first blacksite, it begins adding 1 progress to the meter, up to 12 points in total. After several weeks a new Blacksite will be discovered, and it will add more progress to the bar. Destroying one of them removes its progress from the overall meter by up to three points. Can be unfair at points, but it serves to get your butt into gear fast.Wounds: Any wounds your soldiers get in battle will result in them spending time in the hospital, with time depending on the severity of their injury. Initially, even a graze nets you about a week in the hospital, but some facilities lessen this.Engine: 6/10Loading: This is the biggest pratfall. If you don't have a high end computer, prepare to have something to occupy your time for five minutes at a time, because that's what you're dealing with. Even when you just want to reload your autosave from last turn becuase you had to have killed that sectoid before he mind controls your squad member and DAMMIT AMY, YOU'RE FLANKING HIM, HOW DID YOU MISS? If you have a really good PC, I've heard you can reduce loading times by pressing caps lock, which makes it load all the data at once instead of sequentially or something like that. Use at your own risk.Camera: Four-angle camera, results in the clunkiest of angles when setting up grenade shots and moving in multi-level facilities.Enemy AI: May seem vicious at first, but is actually pretty easy to use against itself, unfortunately most tactics only work twice until it counters it.Overall: 9/10. It may seem daunting at first, but it gets easier. Trust me.P.S: Don't turn on the Alien Hunters DLC missions on on your first playthrough. Not if you value your computer's safety. You will most likely take a hammer to it because WHY DID THE BESEKRER QUEEN HAVE TO SHOW UP TWO TURNS FROM EVAC? WHHYYYYYY?"
