76561198035763897,Recommended,268500,29193100,Posted: 11 January,all,VictoryRpg,"I'll start this off by saying that I've not experienced any gamebreaking bugs or crashes while playing on this machine.  Performance is wierdly inconsistent but is playable.  I can't speak to the experience that others will have.With that out of the way, this is not a good XCOM game, it's a great game, truly fantastic, but it's not a good XCOM game.  That's okay though, the original UFO defense is one of, if not my favorite games of all time.  I own it on multiple platforms and play Openxcom to this day.Where UFO defense was heavily minimalistic mechanically, with most actions following the same set of rules, XCOM 2 has a great variety of additional features.  This gives this game many more areas in which it can fail or seem unpolished, the complexity and volume of unique mechanics being staggering. This isn't always a bad thing, although balancing certain things equally becomes difficult.  This gives you a greater degree of control and customization as regards units, equipment, and tactics.  Your XCOM is very much your XCOM.  In UFO defense your XCOM had very much a mind of its own, soldiers wouldn't advance how you would like, the missions were unfair as♥♥♥♥♥♥ and the main objectives seemed to consciously evade you.XCOM2 does not have that personality, but as a game it is far more ""playable"" than UFO Defense.  You don't need a master's degree in patience and risk management to finish it, and some degree of randomness is removed.  XCOM2 is a handcrafted experience, like a fine Oak table, whereas the original is like a very nice tree that decides to grow through your living room.It is an excellent tactics and management game, perhaps the best of this generation.  I feel that it is almost a disservice to both games, UFO defense being the other, to link them.  This game is unique, well crafted, challenging, and playable.  I very much recommend it."
