,Recommended,268500,21195765,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,master32904,"I have to say that this is one of the most addicting and well designed games I have played in recent memory.  It is nice to see a game put together this well at release.  It IS hard, but not in a cheaty unfair way.  If you're looking for a challenge, then this is the one you want to be playing.  30-ish hours into my frst game and I am only just now getting to a point of relative comfort.Pros:- Lots of fun and innovative ways to kill aliens.- Nice Graphics.- Plenty of character customization. You will get attached to your people, and many will die.- Simple, yet challenging tactical gameplay.  Just rushing in will only get you killed.  Also, there are MANY crucial descisions that always need to be made on the world map and in the Avenger- Its is a challenge, and really captures the essence of a deperate struggle against a much more powerful enemy.- Open for modding.  I wont use mods on my first playthrough (I do have the two DLC's), but I am excited to see what people come up with for this game.  It's sure to be good.Cons:- Mild framerate drops.  This only happens in the pre and post mission sequences in the dropship for me though.  Ive got an NVIDIA GTX 980M 8GB, graphics are on high.  The alien turns hang up sometimes as well, but this is rare.- More stats.  I like stats, so keeping track of all of the character stats would be awesome instead of just missions and kills.I cant give you anything worse than the two minor cons above.Overall 9.5/10"
,Recommended,268500,21196181,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,GrizzlyElk,"A game that rewards smart choices, deep planning, multitasking, finacial and time management, and good calls.You need to be able to play under pressure, play under the odds, and understand that battles will be lost, troops will die, and sometimes it is best to pull out and extract your survivors carrying the dead.Yeah its RNG, yeah there are times where you will miss a 95% chance hit, but thats the thing, don't expect to hit. Prepare your operatives for the next move, not the current.You can't expect to be the best, you can't expect to win, but you can expect a tough and brutal experience where you will have to counter and assume the role as a commander. As you would expect, commanding the last of earths forces against unknown adversaries, under unknown circumstances, where everything is a variable and nothing is set is as hard as you would imagine it to be.Best played on Ironman mode."
,Recommended,268500,21196737,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,black_dragon74,"A worthy addition to the fantastic XCOM series, and a compelling addendum to XCOM: Enemy Unknown.A fantastic game with a fair learning curve, good replayability, and rich storyline (which is largely unnecessary in a setting of ""aliens have invaded, go kill them"", but there you go). As such, I'll mainly be judging the game in comparison to the first one.The new additions are good, and make an effort to appeal to the ""rebel resistance"" theme of the new game. There's hacking, concealment, randomized loot drops, a new resource ""intel"", a remix of the classes, and the XCOM ""base"" now spends its time shooting all over the globe to try and sustain the resistance. Also, many missions now require the squad to complete an objective and extract rather than just giving the player the ""kill all enemies"" mission in different terrain settings. Concealment adds a fantastic new dimension to the tactical game, allowing you to launch ambushes, bypass enemy squads entirely, and scout for your opponents. The new classes all operate very differently from each other, and their abilities are now categorized based on what you want that particular soldier to do: blow stuff up, or support with heavy fire? Scout, or assault? Heal or shut down robotic enemies? Gone are the days where most of your soldiers of a given class took the same upgrades because most were just plain better than the other choice. There's still some of that (I'm never going to NOT take Long Watch or Threat Assessment, guys), but with most of the skills you're making a clear choice between what sort of role they'll play in future battles. Psychic soldiers are also a class of their own now, rather than being ordinary soldiers with additional powers. The Avenger is a neat little change from the single XCOM facility, both in terms of gameplay and theme. It's also nice that the organization is always doing something, rather than the ""scanning"" option that the first game used to fast-forward until something interesting happened.Hacking and looting are less interesting. Neither are particularly tactical, and the loot has that bizarre video-game quality where a chrysalid can apparently come loaded down with weapon attachments. There's also only one enemy in each mission that drops loot, and it can explode if you kill the enemy with explosive weapons or don't get to it in time. These things change the character of each mission, but not in any meaningful or important way.Some things that are missing from the game that were in the last one are alien capturing, shooting down UFOs, and lasers. Laser weapons have been replaced by ""magnetic weapons"" as the second-tier weapon technology, but other than a lack of red beams don't represent any kind of meaningful change. Aliens can't be captured, but don't worry; the game finds other ways to make you charge up to extremely unsafe range and try to punch at enemy troops with the Skulljack. That said, I didn't actually get much use out of it; there are only two occasions in which you have to use it on enemies. The removal of UFO-hunting is quite a blow, and unfortunately takes out a big part of the original XCOM game. There are UFOs, but they're rare, and unlike before don't yield critical supplies and components on the (very uncommon) chance that you actually get to assault one. I realize that the dynamic of the second game makes the idea of XCOM shooting down UFOs with interceptors very unlikely, but considering that scavenging alien technology is supposed to be more important than ever it feels like they could have worked it in somehow.Finally, general criticisms: the research tree is too short, and there aren't enough types of buildings. After having finished the game, I regretted all the investments I'd made into scientists and engineers, because I'd spent the last third of my game time with the scientists standing around doing nothing and two engineers (and room spaces) with nothing to do. I feel like there was definitely room for another technology tier of weapons and armor; how about magnetic, then laser, THEN plasma? And maybe an improved power armor suit for late game? A slew of very late-game projects would have been nice, just to give my scientists something to do. Perhaps give them an option to create PCS upgrades? Or maybe some marginal weapon improvements that have extremely long research times? We need SOMETHING.Some more variety in weapons would also be nice. Just as before, the Assault (now the Ranger) class is the only one that gets a choice of main weapon, and that choice is rifle or shotgun. It's nice that you put a flamethrower in the game at all, but on top of being a one-shot weapon, you make me choose between that and the rocket launcher. COME ON, PEOPLE.Finally, bugs. SOOOOOO many bugs. The vast majority are inexplicable graphical bugs that don't hurt the gameplay; the ""bound"" animation causes constant problems, enemies that have the floor suddenly explode under them freeze and then re-appear instantly on the ground, and every time I killed an Andromedon with overwatch fire I was afraid my computer was going to crash. Sometimes when I got shot the damage counter would just show an empty box, and sometimes my soldiers would get stuck in an unusual animation like being knocked unconscious. There's a lot of work to do, which just seems bizarre in a game with this level of sophistication.I'll be playing through again once some more DLC gets released and we get some more content. Hopefully those falling animations will make it in there in the meantime.As a last note, the final battle was pants-ruiningly intense and incredibly satisfying. But I couldn't understand a single thing the aliens were saying. Good job, guys!"
