76561198102241463,Recommended,268500,33261020,Posted: 4 July,all,oops,"Personally, my only previous experience with XCOM was XCOM: Enemy Unknown.  A fantastic game, if I do say so myself.  Thus, my review may not be as ""educated"" as other reviewers.However, I write this review in the hopes that it'll summarize a casual player's thoughts as well as some of the other critisisms that this game has received, so other potential players know what to get into.The main negative thing that others have commented about with this game is that it rushes the players too much.  I would have to agree.  The main threat that the players must worry about is the ""Avatar Project"", instead of the withdrawl of the globe's support. Unprepared players will be quickly overwhelmed since the project advances rather quickly, compared to the time necessary to actually gain support from the world.  Additionally, many missions have a timer that somewhat diminishes the experience, because you cannot take your time as meticulously as XCOM: Enemy Unknown allowed you to.  An added stealth aspect to some missions seem to suffer from this mechanic, because you cannot playas carefully.On the positive side, I do enjoy this game.  Enemies have been remodelled and redone, there are new classes, maps, tactics, and more micromanagement. It is definitely a harrowing, difficult game that isn't for those who hate stress.  Research is a little more forgiving because upgrades to a unit's armour, weapons, etc. are automatically applied to all troops once built.  Choices made are no longer about which country you can sacrifice some Panic levels in; instead, all consequences directly influence you and your anti-alien facilities.  To some, this may be rather off-putting because again, these consequences can also give the player a sense of ""rushing"", but to me I feel that this adds to the difficulty and gives XCOM 2 a sense of immediate danger instead of indirect, distant consequences.Overall, I recommend this game to people who do not mind stress in their gameplay, an acceptance of failure, and a much more difficult game than XCOM: Enemy Unknown with some familiar mechanics in between."
