76561198006109762,Recommended,268500,26494456,"Posted: 8 November, 2016",all,Radiophonic,"XCOM 2 is a good turn-based game -  I recommend it!GameplayYou race around a map in a very massive aircraft, collecting resources, and taking on missions.  These missions involve shooting aliens.  A large number of missions have timers (which adds a level of difficulty).  If your dudes and dudettes survive, they get more beastly.  You spend lots of time researching and building gear for your soldiers and watching them mend in the hospital after they got shot up in the last mission.  In said missions, Sometimes your soldiers really suck and you get so incredibly furious.  Other times, they totally rock and you well with pride.  There is also a big timer that works against you all game, but I found it pretty lax.  The Proving Ground (a buildable facility) throws an element of randomness into the game by never knowing what the heck those engineers will actually come up with for you (special ammo, grenades, body armour, etc).SquadI really got attached to the squad members in this game. I loved customizing them, changing voice sets, nationality, gender's, etc, to make the right set of killer dolls.  The number of reloads due to key team members biting the bullet was high.  I like the classes available for squad members, of which there are five, each with two skill options to decide between on level up.The psionic class (unlockable by building a facility), has a nice feeling of power and can really rock the alien's world when fully trained.DifficultyI have played all the XCOM's to date and feel that perhaps XCOM UFO Defense (the oldest) was harder, but not by much (and my memory may be failing me, that was a while ago).  I played it through on normal, but had to turn it down to easy on two missions (which felt like cheating, but it was easier!).  Good on ya if you can play it on harder modes, although I didn't try them.BugsIt certainly has a few bugs, but none prevented me from accomplishing anything and at worst made me reload a save.  Mostly, they ocurred in the form of odd misclicks with the UI, a team member not getting off the dropship at mission start, terrain issues, squad members looking but not acting alive when they had been nuked by an alien, etc.  Nothing too important.Time to WreckI took my time, but it was around 35 hours or so from start to finish."
