76561198034630212,Recommended,268500,26956921,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Taco Turtle,"A very good game that not only improves on the previous game but also innovates in the right ways. With expansions, I definately approve, with mods, even better."
,Recommended,268500,31079622,Posted: 11 April,all,pH. mmSNAKE,"Originally I wrote a fairly negative review since I was rather angry with some of the issues that burden this game. I retracted the review since I decided to run a good bit of Long War 2 before I made my decisions. While this review is going to adress vanilla game my decisions are strongly influenced by the mod community and in particular Long War 2. Without that I probably wouldn't play this game ever again.This is a sequel to XCOM: Enemy Unknown, where you lost the fight, and now you fight from a conquered society as rebels. The situation might change but the gameplay overview is still the same. You manage resources, you make research decisions, you manage other 'countries' (havens), build your base, level your troops and so forth. There are various changes and improvements over the previous game. I'm gonna go over those first.One is that most missions you start concealed. This lets you sneak around and perform an ambush on a patrolling enemy squad. This significantly changed the overwatch camping inching from the previous game. You can gather information easier and therefore have more control on when and how you activate a pod. Even if a mission doesn't start you concealed you can bring a soldier that has 'phantom' ability and starts out so nevertheless. Next is Overwatch is FAR better. No more of your entire team shooting at a dead corpse. If one unit kills a target, others won't waste their overwatch shot on it. I can't express how good this change is. Classes in vanilla are similar to those from EU. Perhaps slight tweaks (like support class become a more remote hacker/medic type class), but more or less the same. Psi trooper gets their own specific class, and in vanilla they are probably overpowered once fully online. Long War 2 goes way beyond everything in vanilla, just like in LW1 in comparison.Most aliens make return, but some perhaps with slight changes. Sectoids, Mutons, Berserkers, Sectopods etc. While humanoid ADVENT join and make a bulk of their forces this time around. It will make the engagements different (especially in LW2), when you have humanoids running around with rocket launchers, grenade launchers and have very specific and deadly OW capabilities. Overall tactical flavor in this game is definately not lacking.So what went wrong? The technical portion of the game is a mess. Line of sight bugs are NUMEROUS, and at times can make your mission go down the toilet. Your unit has los on a unit in cover. You destroy that cover, now your unit somehow magically doesn't see the exposed/flanked unit. Or You get cover just 'wearing off'. All of a sudden your unit in full cover stops registering that it is in cover and counts as exposed. There are MANY of dumb instances where game doesn't behave as it is supposed to, clearly buggy behavior. It can ruin missions. If you are playing this game (and LW2) I suggest that you don't run Ironman. I personally am fine with losing troops, I'm fine with making a mistake and activating poorly, but I'm not ok when I lose a mission to a bug.Then there is optimization. Hoo boy is this bad. I have a 1080, i7 7700 and I will get lag spikes in some activations, animations or when particle effects are numerous. Sure it is a turn based game (and Long War 2 has a LOT more♥♥♥♥♥♥than vanilla game), and yeah the game looks pretty good, but not THAT good that it should tax the hardware so much. Honestly unless you crank down every setting and resolution you will probably suffer performance issues with machines that aren't up to snuff.The biggest saving grace for this game is the modding support. There are absurd amount of mods. From amazing quality of life mods (gotcha again), to cosmetic mods, to outstanding UI mods, to complete overhauls like Long War 2 (which i honest consider the base game at this point, since I'm never playing vanilla again). You can also go into the files and tweak setting to how you see fit. Overall this lets you expand and cater the game to how you would like it more to be. More complex, or less. Harder or easier, it is all in your hands.So my overall judgement is if you plan on playing this for vanilla I can't endorse it.  The game doesn't offer enough options and gameplay when faced with such technical issues, but if you want to mod it (doesn't have to be Long War 2), I would then say go for it and you will probably find something you can spend hundreds of hours on."
