,Recommended,268500,34316686,Posted: 17 August,all,[MM]ManS_laughter[UK],XCOM 2 is the strongest game in my library of games. It's a game you can return to again and again because the enjoyment is from facing against a strong challenge and bringing home a well earned victory again and again.A lot of people have complained about the turn timers for missions but ultimately the reason for the timers is to put the player on the back foot and force them not only to defeat the enemy but to take risks. These are the sort of risks that an underground resistance movement would have to take. Losing a mission isn't game over by any means - you can even lose an entire well trained team on a mission and still recover a campaign. The people who are really hurt are the people who think that only 100% victory on every single mission counts as success. You can complain that the timers are unfair but this is a game about succeeding against an unfair opponent.In every way XCOM 2 improves on XCOM - it is an incredibly detailed puzzle game where balancing risk and reward is key. If you think you can achieve success without risk you will be punished ultimately. Your rookies might miss easy shots but if you are a good commander you will find a way to turn the sum total of all those shots into a success.
