,Recommended,268500,28957861,Posted: 2 January,all,Faheelee,"Upfront TL;DR:I recommend XCOM2 to anyone who is remotely interested in strategy/tactical rpg games and does not mind a few hiccups in optimization.It is like a sci-fi Fire Emblem without anime cutscenes and support convos (all that waifu♥♥♥♥♥♥ and adds good graphics and destructible environments.XCOM2's plot is the classic Good vs. Evil with some philosophical drops of ""we are becoming what we set out to destroy"".The real story, however, is the success and failure of XCOM agents under your command.BTW If you can't play a game without your precious waifus then download a voice pack for them and add them to your character pool. Pretty sure there are a bunch of neptunia heads and voice packs in the workshop. See, everyone's happy.Introduction:This review is tailored for those who have not played any iteration of XCOM, so that it better informs those interested in trying the game out.Before continuing, I want to say that mods are a double edged sword in this game. They enhance play and decrease performance at the same time (subscribed to 300 atm). I cannot deny the fantastic additions graced to XCOM2 by the modding community, but I hope to review the ideas and concepts that the vanilla version succeeded/failed to accomplish on its own.Specs:i7-6700K @ 4.00GHz (4.36GHz)16 GB RAMGTX 1070Pros:+The ability to extensively customize your soliders contributes a sense of attachment to  soldiers you are ordering around, something most games cannot emulate.+Map generation is very well designed/balanced so that the same tileset/area can offer many different avenues of play.+Configurable settings via the xcom ini can further modify play, leading to more replayability. For example, you can change the base stats of every character/item in the game if you wanted.+There is some base management, but it is not too extensive and does not feel tacked on just because ""every other game has some form of it"" (the original XCOM had this too).+Combat is interesting and offers different approaches to problems through the soldier class system, plethora of researchable gear, and destructible environments.+The emphasis on limited time (in combat and on a macro scale) to rebel against Earth's alien overlords provides a sense of urgency that many games strive for yet miss.+Your soldiers and the aliens become stronger as the game goes on, which creates a sense of each side trying its hardest to defeat the other.+Countless workshop mods offer something new and exciting to experience through multiple playthroughs.+There is an ironman mode (Only one save state) for tryhards. Variable difficulty as well, which is good for new players.+A game that discourages facerolling over every button on your keyboard.Cons:-You have to realize this game has its optimization issues.-Loading screens can be long, depending on your settings and how many mods you decide to download. I think the base game does not have this problem as much as a heavily modified one.-Frame rate drops slightly when discovering enemies, unloading from your transport, and initializing props to customize your soldiers with. These frame rate issues, however, can be easily ignored since they only occur at specific points in the game and do little to hinder the gameplay itself.-Do not play at max settings, even the best rigs will have trouble stabilizing at that golden 60fps.-Due to the nature of XCOM2, it being quite a long game, these problems seem to be more apparent later on when there are simply more characters in a given mission (larger squad size, more enemies, etc.).-There are not many gameplay elements that I feel XCOM2 failed to deliver on, but indeed there are many annoyances within the vanilla version that have either been patched already or allieviated by the free mods inside the workshop.Conclusion:So if you do buy the game and see something that is offputting, check out the workshop to see if a solution has already been distributed.More than likely if you see something as a problem, someone else has too.This concludes my review of XCOM 2. If you made it this far, then congratulations on either scrolling fast or reading."
,Recommended,268500,21005652,"Posted: 6 February, 2016",all,Zanteogo,"First thing, the difficultly level, for me, is fine at the default. Perhaps I just suck.  ;)I love how many of the old systems from the last Xcom have been carried over but in some cases improved. Having reload of your weapon not end your turn for example.Somethings, I'm not sure about.The will loss (from taking damage?) that recovers from doing well at a future mission is annoying. Thankfully panic is much less of a mission ender.The aliens start with some pretty powerful abilities from the get go this time. One thing that I didn't like, is the early mind control. When you have a squad of 4 it's a big deal. You hardly ever resist it. It can even end your mission if your entire squad is mind controlled. The only saving grace is that the aliens won't damage mind controlled teammates, so sometimes it actually saves you. (when a surprised flanked unit gets taken for example) edit: actually, they will target mind controled units if they have nothing else to shot at.My biggest beef with the game is how the timed missions with random maps work. You will have X amount of time to do something and get to a certain point. However, because the maps are random, sometimes that point can be so hard to get to that even if you ignored the aliens and dashed right for it your cutting it close. I don't mind the rush effect sometimes, but I like to take my time and do things systematically. They need to have at least one more turn added to them across the board.Moving units to different levels is STILL a pain. I have had units run to the wrong point because it's hard to tell exactly what level your selecting your space on. A couple of pods activated through walls too.It's overall a good game. It needs to be tweaked somewhat however. Thankfully it's supposed to be super mod friendly, so we will see. I suggest to anyone who loved the last XCOM, to get this one. It is good game overall."
76561198170144287,Not Recommended,268500,23608209,"Posted: 16 June, 2016",all,Zwvn,"This game could have been awesome.It does not give nearly enough time to complete anything without failing critical missions. If you do focus on critical missions and skip most upgrades and research, you will be vastly outnumbered and far from powerful enough. I do not have a whole lot of turn-based strategy gaming experience, but even on the EASIEST setting (which is suggested in-game for non-experienced players), the difficulty scales way too fast with your progress and quickly becomes impossible. The tutorial gave hardly any hints and tips, leaving the player to figure everything out on their own whilst getting their butt kicked. There are also strategy-critical BUGS throughout the game that tilt to the enemies advantage (for example, enemies shooting through two walls before they are destroyed, or enemies slashing your squad members from below you). A 4-man squad is absolutely ridiculous when you have many more soldiers to spare, especially when going up against 10+ enemy units. The Dark Events are also relentless and make the enemy much too powerful. It is also frustrating that there is no way to take the time to counter all the Dark Events. In fact, you can't ""take the time"" to do much at all. The entire game rushes the player through everything, interupting progress with side missions that are far too detrimental to lose. There are also several aspects that don't make sense and uselessly inhibiting of a good game experience.Now that I've got that off my chest, here's what I find amazing about this game.The platform is easy to use. Graphics, landscape, splash art, the alien concepts, these are all beautiful and very attractive. This game has a unique blend of action and story progression, which I find very enjoyable. The aliens themselves are decently authentic and fun to discover and fight. All of this alone ALMOST makes up for the rest of my frustrating experience.Conclusion:This game was a complete joy to learn about and explore for several hours, but became a complete mess of failure and frustration rather quickly. I have a bit of regret paying $60 for this. I'm sure there is a very specific way to play this game and do quite well, but it is not obvious at all. I do not enjoy having to go research how to actually play to feel as though my purchase is worth (which I will do now) and would much rather be able to learn and explore everything myself with a successfully challenging experience. Perhaps my review will change once I do some digging.4/10"
