76561198044404117,Recommended,268500,34721032,Posted: 3 September,all,Veldren,"Got it for $25 on a Steam sale, and it is worth every bit of that and more if you are a fan of strategy games in general and XCOM in particular. It is a bit different as the Sectoids and stuff aren't the same standard X-Files aliens like in the original or anything like that, but there is a lot improved here as well.It does feel more difficult than the original, and I've bumped back down to Rookie difficulty so as not to get totally murdered. Don't let that thwart you though. The new things like having a Ranger class that can go melee with a sword is a great addition to your tactical toolbox, as are the psionics. Those are actually quite powerful and I'm pleased to take them along now.I haven't completed it yet, but I'm not in a rush to either. One thing I remember seeing was that there were time limits and it somehow ruined the game. Let me tell you that the turn limits in a battle are actually reasonable and logical: get X before Y happens, that sort of thing. A few of those were in XCOM and while you might want to play around on a map, frankly the longer you drag a mission out the more likely you are to end up with a roster of injured soldiers. Get in, get it, get out, just like you would if you were really doing this. As far as the campaign itself, that is no different than the Doomsday clock or whatever, except with the Avatar project you can actually take away the enemy's progress.When you do have time to spare - and honestly you usually do - setting up ambushes is a super effective way to take out enemies quickly. Concealment and overwatch ambush is too good to pass up.The storyline is interesting and I'm intrigued by the build-up to whatever this big revelation is going to be. They definitely have some neat ideas going.The only negatives I might mention really are the interruptions. You're trying to scan or pass time on the map  but every few seconds there is a chain of stuff going on. Most of it is research or construction, sometimes notifications about new missions, other times required events that you need to handle. It's better than scanning for weeks and hoping a UFO comes down but yeah, just a minor complaint.Overall: Seriously if you're wondering if it's for you, give it a try. Steam offers sales frequently enough that you could put it on your wishlist and grab it later. It is a good game, and it annoys me that I fell prey to negative reviews and held off. To be fair, it might have been rough before, and updates have patched various bugs."
