76561198077801335,Recommended,268500,29968833,Posted: 16 February,all,Kn1VeS,"Xcom 2 is a welcome return for the series that builds on the foundations of enemy unknown and within, while adding a host of new mechanics that make for a great turn-based strategy game. On the plus side, Xcom 2 sticks to the challenging formula of its predecessors, having players engage in turn-based combat with a global strategy element to tie missions together. Mission objectives range from escorting VIP characters to safe zones, eliminating enemies across the map, and capturing important zones etc.The sound, voice and music is great. Noteworthy are the voice actor performances of both the player controlled characters, as well as the advent (alien) enemies you will slaughter in droves.The strongest element of Xcom 2 is its addictive gameplay. I found myself always wanting to have one more turn, complete one more research objective or take control of one more region. The impetus to always progress forward is key to the Xcom 2 experience. However the game can become repetitive, especially near the campaigns end, where having to blow up one more advent facility became a tedious chore.Xcom 2’s story is average at best and doesn’t add much to the overall experience. It does its job to string several missions together, but could have been better. But hey, when has an Xcom game been carried by its story? Note: The dlc missions do add some extra flavor to the campaign by introducing characters from the past Xcom games. But these missions are few and far between.The game's enemies are a contentious point for me. Their design is topnotch, having a wide array of abilities that will confound and challenge the player throughout the 25+ hour campaign. However, the enemy AI can change with a flip of a coin, often performing game winning actions one moment, then throwing themselves into the line of fire for no apparent reason in the next. Note: The alien ruler dlc adds three superior enemies that are absolutely devastating, having abilities that can seem quite unfair on harder difficulties.A sore point throughout my experience with the game is the fact that the game suffers from many bugs and performance issues, even after a year’s worth of patches. Frame rate dips are still common and occasionally the game does crash, even more so when playing with mods that may conflict with one another. It is also notable that I ran into a wide variety of issues across three different pc setups.Overall, Xcom 2 presents that same acclaimed experience that earlier Xcom titles introduced, but does so with a more flashier and exciting feel to it. Even with a host of problems that the game suffers from, I still love this title and recommend it to anyone who enjoys challenging turn-based strategy games. 8.6/10"
