,Recommended,268500,21064647,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,Robin,"Awesome game. An improvement I didn't think was possible from Enemy Unknown.The story is deep and the missions are ruthless.There clearly are some people whom are having trouble adjusting their play to the new timed scenarios but I'd say that they are without a doubt the best thing to happen to UFO/XCOM in a long time, especially so if you like playing on Iron Man. The reason is that they force your hand to action. You are no longer able to play ridiculously defensively going inch by inch through the level with all your guys always on overwatch but are going to have to make some really tough calls.Sometimes you'll make the wrong call, people will die, sometimes you'll make the right call and people will die anyway. Sometime leaving your guys to die is  the right call in the longer campaign. Previously Iron Man was simply an excercise in patience, since there were heavy consequences to having your guys shot at, the valid strategy was the one spent hammering overwatch and end turn never putting any of your guys at risk. If you never put anybody at risk, you don't need to load save games.In XCOM2, this is a luxury you seldom have. Usually there is something pressing you on, be it a beacon calling in enemy reinforcement, civilians getting eaten by aliens, a bomb timer ticking or just hordes and hordes of enemy reinforcements whittling you down. This calls for action and decisiveness, but if you over-extend and act too hastily, the game will still be there to punish your overconfidence.There are some missions where there is no timer or the timer will start very late in the mission or the timer might not start until you leave concealment (more about this later). These are usually the missions with the stiffest resistance as well. It allows you to revel in these occasions to really cheese the aliens as much as you can, pay them back for past transgressions, savor the ambush. (Un)fortunately these are also the missions where the aliens are the most well equipped to raise you on your cheese and give you a run for your money. The first such mission I ran into the only survivor was a sole rookie, objective in hand, runnning for her life from hordes of alien reinforcements. The mission was a success albeit a pyrrhic one as my best sniper, my best ranger and my last grenadier were left dead on the battlefield.Other pros:- The whole setting being insurgents against a state of dystopian alien opressors is awesome and surprisingly(!) fits the gameplay much better than the original secret government agency schtick that most other x-com games have had.- The new concealment system allows for some glorious ambushes though it doesn't hand it to you on a silver platter, you really have to be clever about it utilise it to it's full.- The game seems a lot longer and more content rich than previous Firaxis x-com games, that being said there is some heavy borrowing here and there especially on the gear side, but all in all more is more and there are few things without some new refinement.- The base building and management of the avenger (flying around doing missions on the map) feels a lot more refined and is more fun than in previous games. Also, it's no longer just about MOAR LABS, MOAR SCIENTISTS! Engineers are really nice and have a lot of versatility and tasks to balance.- There is a lot more verticality in the missions, allowing better and more varied level design.- Voice acting is good and the characters in your base have a lot of non-critical monologue/reflectections that are fun to listen to but easy to skip.- All aliens are ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥sCons:- All aliens are ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥s- The user interface feels very laggy at times, especially during combat.- The framerate will suffer at times, more so than you'd expect from a turn based game. With that being said though, since it's a turn based game it's not a game breaker, but somewhat of an annoyance.- The game has a significant amount of minor bugs, nothing game breaking or super annoying though- The line of sight system is supposed to be super simple, but it turns out instead to be very unpredictable at times as it sometimes allows enemies and players to shoot through walls (it at least makes holes in the wall when they do). Also, what counts as cover from what angles is kinda gamey and you can have situations where it looks like you can clearly see an enemy but it turns out he's in heavy cover. The rules for when they are or are not are rather simple, so you can learn them but it does take you out of the moment sometimes.- You can only rotate the camera in 90 degree increments and have very low zoom in/out capabilities. I suspect this is due to the line of sight thing, since trying to look down from where your character is looking won't actually help you tell if there'll be line of sight or not.- Sometimes, especially when fighting in enclosed spaces, the wall transparence effect that's supposed to allow you to see what you're doing even if there's a wall between you and your character will also make the wall behind your character transparent making it very hard to see what's where and where there are walls and where there aren't.Overall, great game. I was pleasantly surprised despite high expectations."
