,Recommended,268500,23907206,"Posted: 28 June, 2016",all,HalfBurntToast,"So far, I feel like this game improves on 2012 XCOM in just about every way. The game is more engaging, more tense, and more difficult. Yeah, I finished Enemy Unknown thinking, “you know, that wasn't so bad towards the end, I might actually be getting good at XCOM.” Less than two hours into the game, I realize that I SUCK at XCOM. I'm currently playing on easy (after starting on normal) and save scumming without remorse. This game is absolutely brutal bordering on unfair at times. The difficulty does vary a lot depending on how the level generates and an unfortunate spawn location/enemy spawn/objective/etc can make your missions take a wrong turn very easily. That said, once you get the ball rolling with your squad, the missions definitely become much less of a meat grinder. I'll probably be replaying this on higher difficulty after I finish the story. It does feel a bit overwhelming at first with all the resources and timers you have to watch. But, it's not as big of a deal as it first appears and the “lose by timer” has yet to happen for me. You can't sit around and camp like in EU/EW.There are a few issues.  Some of the mission timers are pretty silly (like if your squad is still concealed the timer is still ticking), but most of the timers I'm alight with. There are some weird delays in the game during loading screens, even on a SSD. The performance, while 98% of the time is fine, can get a little chunky at certain points, even on a i5-6600 and GTX970, which will probably be a lot more noticeable on older machines. But, I've only had this game crash to desktop once so far, compared to a countless number of crashes I had in EU. There's also still this weird resistance from other countries in supporting the XCOM project, like in 2012 XCOM with countries leaving (why would they do that at all?). But, I guess it's more believable this time around because of the role-reversal.All in all, this game is awesome and well worth the money."
