76561198010602229,Recommended,268500,21046307,"Posted: 7 February, 2016",all,FRÖZTRÖLL,"There are very few games I've come back to seeking that vicious cycle of: glory, hubris, pain, regret, dread, and glory again and again. I don't see myself as a masochist, but since XCOM: Enemy Unknown, I've found myself hungering for games that remind I'm not that I'm king of the world, but still make me feel like it whenever I conquer it's mounting challenges. Even after Enemy Unknown's initial launch in 2012, I found myself playing it again and again even after beating it the first time, not to mention with the equally exciting Enemy Within expansion in 2013. I didn't think another game would give me that same sense of accomplishment and make me fight to attain it, but I was wrong.In 2016, XCOM 2 reminds me again and again why I love this franchise.XCOM 2 is not XCOM: Enemy Unknown. Sure, it cover-based shooting and powerful alien weaponry mixed with dice rolls and failed 96% shots, but this game more than Enemy Unknown keeps you constantly wishing you were everywhere at once. XCOM 2 doesn't run you through every single system like EU, and some systems won't be as apparent the first time around, but failure and learning are one and the same here. I died a little when I realized the plate armor upgrade carried over to my entire personnel after several hours of playing and several more casualties had already transpired.But I realized how deftly X2 ripped off the training wheels when I couldn't simply sell off my wares to the Gray Market right before a crucially timed mission across the continent.That being said, some additions to the game make combating the alien-infested earth a much more attainable task. I was unsure of how much the concealment mechanic would change my playstyle, or if I would take advantage of it at all. But there is almost nothing more satisfying than setting up an overwatch ambush and seeing the aliens drop from your well placed death-nest of sniper shots and cannon fire.I can ramble on and on about this game, and once I have finished the game I'll be able to confirm if my mad ravings are more than just a fanatical sales-pitch or rose-tinted ad libs. Until then, it's good to be back. I for one will be playing this game for a very long time, and enjoying the regretful deaths and mistakes every step of the way."
