76561198007310186,Recommended,268500,21185568,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,ThreeDog Knight,"+++Edited Feb 27 for Summary+++1. Similar mechanics to XCom EU, reskinned mostly for the better2. Awesome tactical combat3. Annoying mechanics that interrupt gameplay4.  Someone shoot Bradford (There are mods that will shut him up)5.  Expanded use of mission timers adds tension, but to me it feels heavyhanded (again, can be modded out).++++++Okay, I am not going to say that this game is flawless.  In fact, by time this is over (if you read all of my review) you might think I hate the game due to its annoyances, but you would be wrong.  It's another awesome XCOM game.Despite the big change in the premise, the game mechanics are much like the XCOM from a few years back.  The premise is that you lost the original XCOM game, the commander (you) got captured and was imprisoned by the evil aliens who set up a velvet gauntlet world government.  Some of  XCOM remains as a resistance who fights the aliens with little success for 20 years.  The 'some remaining' part is Central Officer Bradford, who in the previous game was your chief of staff who briefed you on missions and showed up in a lot of cutscenes.  They re-voiced actored and reskinned him so that he went from a pencil neck support guy to some generic G.I. Joe type.  For some reason, Bradford decides that they only way the resistance can survive is to rescue the guy who lost the last war for them (you), and that's where the game begins.The guts of the game will be very familiar to players of the old game.  You have a squad of up to six members.  Instead of an underground base that you can expand to add new capabilites, you have a mobile spaceship that you clear out to add new capabilities.  Instead of a doom clock tracking angry countries who turn their back on XCOM, you have a sinister alien project that fills in little red boxes - when they are all filled the game ends, but if you do specific missions you can un-fill boxes.  Instead of building facilties to launch satellites to add countries and their revenue, in XCOM2 you add comm rooms to spread your defiant message to new areas of the subjugated world.  You also reasearch and build new technologies to upgrade your squad's weapons, like in the old game.Some of the tinkering changes I like.  The have new classes, which are also mostly improvements.  Some are familiar, but the speicalist is a big change that worked for me.  Like the orignal, most classes generally have two training tracks -- specialists can focus on taking out mechanical creatures (vital in this game) or healing your squad.  But also, they have some decent general combat cacabilities such as some overwatch bonuses.  They are also the best at hacking enemy facilities and possibly getting good personal or squad bonues.  Or, if they screw up, they can give the aliens adantages.The changes to base building are generally good too. In the old game if you wanted new scientists or engineers, you either bought them through facility upgrades, or got them through missions.  They were all faceless and nameless.  In XCOM2, you can recruit them from places on the map or rescue them from missions.  They all have names and their own appearce.  Moreover, they changed how engineers work.  In the old XCOM they were part of an equation on how fast you build stuff and were packed into the labs like Jack's Links in an economy pack.  Now, you can upgrade the effectivness of most of your facilties by assigning an specific engineer to a specific facility.  This is kind of scary when you assign an engineer to the med bay so your soldiers will heal faster.  Dear Firaxis:  Ability to build bridge does not equal ability to perform surgery on human being.In general, the base building I think is an improvement on the old XCOM, but the combat, which is the meat and drink of XCOM is still good - in fact it's better.  I have never had as many fun, interesting tactical challenges and fun responses to those challenges as I have experienced in this game.   The different ways of opening up a can on alien butt is astounding.  I personally like explosions, so I carry a squad heavy in grenadiers who strip away armor and weaken the bad guys so my other squad members can mop up.  They also added more useful pistol skills to the sharpshooter to give them more tactical flexibility.  Rangers have some pretty amazing close quarter skills, and psi guys can unload lots of white-haired, purply awesomness.  There is a thread on the forums about favorite XCOM2 moments that will demonstrate just how versatile, fun and rewarding the combat is.Some parts of the game are no so much fun.  The game seems to be designed to too frequently rip the controls out of your hands and show you things that you already know or don't care about.  For example, most of the strategic game involves flying to a part of the world map to pick up supplies, start missions, etc.  These actions typically take time.  While you are doing this, the game keeps interrupting you to tell you about side missions, new supplies, or alien progress in their doomsday weapon.  It doesn't do this by just having a message on the screen or an announcement -- no, it highjacks your screen through a cutscene or force-scrolls you over to some other part of the map like the middle of the pacific or wherever.  Then you have to manually scroll back to whatever you we doing.  It does this a lot, and its annoying.Second, I am not sure why the world got overrun after XCOM, but I'm going to blame Bradford.  Not because its his fault or anything, but because he is an annoying, bossy little twit.  Even more than XCOM, his voiceover druing missions is aggravating.  For example, there are missions where the aliens are attacking reistance settlements.  To 'win' the mission, the aliens can't kill more than 6 civilians.  At civilian death #1 he starts screaming that the civilan casusalties are ""massive"" AND YOU MUST DO SOMETHING NOW.  He does this several times again in this mission as more unfortunates on the other side of the map die.  He also similarly hyperventalates during every other timer mission.    When you are in a nasty firefight while he is at home in his comfy chair, it gets a little hard to take.On this issue of timers, there has already been a lot written so I won't spend much time on them except to say I have mixed feelings.  I played vanilla throughout my first playthrough and disliked being on the clock.  Also, XCOM is a tactical game about squad combat.   I don't think charging into 60% of all missions at full bore while some desk jocky screams ""Hurry, hurry, hurry.  My god, the damage, the casulaties..."" into your ear is the culmination of 2000 years of tactical doctrine.  However, I never really had a problem meeting the deadlines, and a part of me also says the combat would not be as fun and as engaging without that artifical sense of drama.  On my next playthrough I've decided not to load one of the mods that extend or remove the timers.  But you can if you want, its really up to you.In short this game is a must for anyone who likes tactical, turn-based combat, and I hope you enjoy it as much as I do."
