,Recommended,268500,34737189,Posted: 4 September,all,ENGLAND is MY CITY!,Not gonna sleep a whileBye GF
,Recommended,268500,21199242,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,Soldant,"XCOM 2 is a worthy yet buggy sequel to 2012's XCOM. It's more challenging (sometimes artificially so) with an overall better sense of urgency and desperation than the original had. Firstly, the game in its current state (Feb 2016) requires patching. There are frequent slow-downs, weird pauses between turns, and the occasional lengthy loading time. The game has trouble maintaining a stable FPS. A lot of these issues were actually present in XCOM 2012's release though and they were (mostly) patched out. Give them time to fix it.In terms of gameplay the core elements of the XCOM francise remain the same - strategic decision-making with turn-based tactical combat against an alien threat. The Geoscape strategic portion has the biggest changes with more choice of ""missions"" which often serve to take up time rather than being tactical missions. For example you can search for supplies or alien materials. Tactical missions pop up with some defined benefit for their completion and a penalty for ignoring them - and the penalty at least up until the end game is punishing, so you often can't ignore them. The game will infrequently give you a choice of 3 missions - these missions will negate one of the bonuses that the aliens acquire for that month. The aliens play a much better strategic game and you can't simply sit and wait for the next plot point to trigger. In XCOM 2012 you could halt progress by simply not completing some objectives, giving you all the time in the world to advance. In XCOM 2 the aliens are constantly making progress on Avatar, their final solution to humanity. You can delay it but you cannot stop it. This increases that urgency and desperation that XCOM desperately needed; you can't simply wait and research your way to victory.The tactical game remains largely the same with the added benefit of better map randomisation, a more aggressive AI, and a few new mechanics. Firstly some missions start you troops in concealment, giving you the ability to move around the map without triggering the enemy unless you get too close (or they patrol into your group), allowing you to set up ambushes. Many missions also have a turn limit. I can see why they did this - a very popular tactic in the original was simply to put everyone into Overwatch and advance cautiously, creating a wall of reaction-fire death. Turn limits stop you from relying on this tactic; you have to find the enemy and objectives quickly instead of creeping forward. Overwatch is still useful but you need to be more aggressive. That said, some of the limits feel awfully restrictive, especially at higher difficulty levels (especially when the aliens are just plain stronger across the board). There are still plenty of ""XCOM fail"" moments where shots miss despite a high probably of hitting (90% isn't 100% guys!) but they hurt a lot more with the new aliens.Overall I actually do recommend XCOM 2 to fans of the original. Plenty of people complain about turn limits, and they do have a point - but plenty of people whinged that XCOM 2012 was too easy with its Overwatch death-squad tactic, so I guess some people just won't be happy either way. There are some technical issues that will no doubt be mostly resolved, but this is still a fantastic game. Incidentally, the original XCOM's successor, Terror from the Deep, was well known for being XCOM except underwater and with a much higher difficulty level. I guess they just followed the same plan this time."
