,Recommended,268500,20986305,"Posted: 5 February, 2016",all,SlyNic,"This is my review so far... NOTE: That I still have a lot to play, but I wanted to share my first impressions!It's quite rare, that the sequel to a multi award winning game, can not only improve on the flaws of its predecessor, but also ""in ways"" manage to be a better game. But the newest installment from the 2k Games 'XCOM' franchise, does exactly that! XCOM 2 brings players back into an action packed, turn based, strategy experience that new & familiar players are sure to enjoy. With heaps of new content helping shape one of the best (if not the best) installment in the 'XCOM' franchise! Below, are some of the things that I really like about XCOM 2...- ""So far..."" An interesting story & campaign- Greatly Improved UI (in my opinion...)- Surprisingly... ALot more draw back to 'XCOM: Enemy Unkown', than I was expecting.- Unpredictability, enemies are no longer as easy to prejudge with their attacks, makes for more interesting gameplay and combat scenarios.- LOTS of Class abilities and skills, all of these are unique to certain troops as well!- The Game Looks amazing, and the cutscenes are great!- ""ROV-R"" is SO COOL!- Greatly improved AI, the AI is both fair and challenging- Heaps of content!XCOM 2 manages to excel in many areas that the previous titles in the 'XCOM' franchise have failed to do so. XCOM 2 is a great game, and players are sure to get heaps of play and enjoyment out of it, considering your into turn based strategy... If you enjoyed 'XCOM: Enemy Unknown', this is the game for you!"
,Recommended,268500,21062141,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,nacon,"XCOM 2 is everything that you loved about XCOM: Enemy Unknown and XCOM: Enemy Within… but better. You will again find yourself in the position of the “Commander,” managing both strategic assets on your mobile base, and your soldiers in tactical actions on missions in the fight against aliens who have taken over Earth.The game largely takes place within these two spheres – strategic, and tactical.In the strategic side of things, players will have to make choices on the Geoscape and within the Avenger.The Geoscape allows you expand your ‘resistance’ contacts, unlocking missions in new areas, chase rumors of supplies and intelligence, and view the progress of the “Game Over” counter that is constantly ticking upwards, against you. The choices on what to pursue are meaningful, as you generally can’t do it all; missions will expire after a set time. Investing time into improving the areas you’ve contacted provides a significant amount of long-term benefit in terms of resource income in the form of ‘supplies’ (your money), at the expense of other missions which might provide more short-term gains.The Avenger gameplay will consist largely of managing your base; much like XCOM: Enemy Unknown, you have a fixed area in which to build, and you must clear out alien debris and plan your structures out within that space. There are more optimal placements if you want to conserve the power necessary to operate your facilities, or to boost your existing power generation structures. There is enough space to construct everything; it’s more a matter of prioritizing which research structures you want over others. While constructing and managing your facilities, you will have the option of re-assigning engineers that you’ve  picked up on missions to increase facility construction speed, upgrade facility roles (generating more power, healing soldiers faster), or make item construction faster. This represents an interesting worker-placement challenge, as you will not have enough engineers to have everything fully upgraded and working at full speed. It is necessary to move engineers from one task to another task as needs change/arise. You will also spend time prioritizing which research you want to pursue, and which experimental weapons/armors/items you would like to make (they’re not all insta-build.)The tactical gameplay utilizes a squad of 4-6 highly customizable soldiers (XCOM operatives) to complete various missions. This will be very familiar to XCOM: Enemy Unknown players; combat takes place on a grid, with various structures and obstacles to use in the fight against the alien menace. Unlike previous games, there is a significantly greater amount of urban combat, and far fewer “fighting in the woods” type missions. The action is well-paced, and well-calculated choices will make the difference in ensuring you leave missions without too many casualties. Many missions have timers associated with them to force you to take an aggressive stance on the tactical map; this is overall an improvement, in my opinion, as previous games allowed a much slower pace (to the detriment of the action of combat.) During missions you will also have the opportunity to pick up gear that your enemies drop; this too is on a timer, incentivizing aggressive action to pick up powerful upgrades. Enemy A.I. is much improved over previous versions, and enemies will tactically retreat to their comrades if they’re overwhelmed. The enemy variety is also very interesting – you will have to adjust tactics, frequently, based on the variety of alien soldiers that you will face.Overall, the game is very difficult, especially in the early months where you are constantly out-gunned and pressured into tough missions to make ends meet. There is a constant tension on missions where you are working against a timer, and there is a near constant tension on the geo-scape as you are forced to choose between equally compelling missions. If you expect to walk into a game and dominate it on the first try, you really won't be able to in XCOM 2.  Learning the nuances of the mechanics of the strategic gameplay and the enemies your facing (along with the squad that you carefully build up) will allow you to remove a lot of the randomness that you'll face, but you will lose soldiers, or have to retreat from certain missions; soldiers, at the end of the day, are a strategic asset that you will sometimes need to sacrifice in order to complete an important strategic goal on your missions. The challenge can be daunting, but eventually you'll get the hang of it and be able to run very smooth  missions that allow you to take on very difficult setups.Plot-wise, the game is well-written and compelling as you try to lead Earth in a rebellion against your alien overlords. Overall, I don’t think that the supporting cast was as well-developed as in previous games; Lily and Tygan are interesting enough, but don’t seem to have the same flair that Shen and Vahlen had in the original. Bradford returns, a bit gruffer, a bit grumpier, but perhaps not as funny as in XCOM: Enemy Unknown. The role and personality of the Commander play a greater part of this game, interestingly enough. The trajectory that humanity is on, and the fate of the Earth are interesting enough in this post-alien dystopia; exploring and seeing details of what that future entails are one of the joys of the game.Graphics-wise, this game is more intense than its predecessors; even with a good medium-end rig, you can expect some slowdowns/framerate drops if maps get too hectic. The environments, textures, and characters are all wonderfully detailed in this future sci-fi dystopia. The world itself has a lot of personality as you conduct missions within it, whether you’re aiding an isolated rural Resistance base, or running a high-powered mission into the heart of A.D.V.E.N.T.-controlled territory.Overall, the game is a worthy successor to XCOM: Enemy Unknown. I look forward to the DLC installments for this game, and I feel there is a great deal of replayability in this particular game. I highly recommend this game to anyone with a PC!"
