,Recommended,268500,21186268,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,Dr. Hans Steiner,"Right off the bat, XCOM 2 is an excellent game. It does everything possible to expand on XCOM: Enemy Unknown, and gives us a great continuation of the story as a whole. The gameplay is a refined version of the RTS tactical shooter from Enemy Unknown, with a whole bunch of new abilities thrown in. The 5 main classes don't feel restrictive and have abilities that can specialize them, so you can always have a soldier to fit your specific mission needs. The classic ""That's XCOM baby!"" line about crazy RNG shots that kill your soldiers is back and more accurate than ever. You can customize your soldiers to your liking, get attached to them as you follow their career, then hold back your emotions when you see them killed by a bad roll of the dice. While sad, the customization is great for different squad builds based on your favorite characters from other shows. I had several squaddies based off Luke Skywalker, Han, Finn, Rey, and others. Not many survived though. The Character Pool is a wonderful addition and I can't wait to see what other characters are made in the community and through mods.The main complaint I have of course is the performance issues I'm having. The build I'm running is:GTX 760 graphics cardInstalled on SSDAMD FX4130 Quad-Core processcor8 GB RAMI should be able to run on the higher settings but the framerate drops significantly and there are frequent stalls when the enemy turn is loading. The more enemies on the field, the slower it goes. Not to mention fires and other secondary effects that eat up renndering time. I also would have trouble seeing in buildings sometimes, particularly in landed UFOs, and occasionally would need to get creative with camera placement. Free camera rotation is a mod now, but it really should have been in the main game.I run the game on minimal and low now to help keep it running more smoothly, but that shouldn't be necessary. I can run it on high with a smoother framerate, but I need to mess with other settings to compensate. This is pretty disappointing overall and can be frustrating at times. In the 60+ hours I've played since release, I've only crashed once or twice. That's not bad, but still falls in with the other performance issues.That said, the framerate really doesn't bother me much since it's a turn based strategy game. You can take your time on your turn and the framerate only drops when you can't do anything anyway. The cutscenes for the story are smooth and helped tell the story of the Resistance.The thrill you can get from this game is just wonderful. I just finished my Veteren Ironman run and every turn felt like it could cost you the game. Very often I found myself in situations where I was sure my squad was going to be disintegrated before my eyes, but then was able to flip the tables and come back (or mitigate the damage with a few brave sacrifices).Overall I really enjoyed this game and I think the whole team do deserve praise for building on their previous title and crafting an excellent RTS game. I hear they are working on the performance issues so that should ideally be fixed soon. I would absolutely recommend this game for anyone loving strategy games or sci fi stories."
76561198044531944,Recommended,268500,20977783,"Posted: 5 February, 2016",all,Otacon,Miss Simulator 2016 is back.
,Recommended,268500,20978790,"Posted: 5 February, 2016",all,ChineseBunInvasion,"TL; DR:Let's get this out of the way quickly.There are irrefutably some performance problems with the game, the framework has clearly not been entirely optimized which can lead to disparate results over a wide number of machines. However, some of these are easily solvable on my configuration. The temporary go-to fix is to turn off anti-aliasing, turn off action camera and if the problem still persists turn off v-sync as well.Past those problems this is the game that was marketed and ultimately delivered to the consumer. The game looks and feels almost exactly like how it was advertised. Which is a refreshing change considering the gray market dealings that most developers have been engaging in over the past couple of years. A breathe of fresh air.I sincerely believe that given a little bit more spit and polish, this could very well be the game that catapults the XCOM franchise to being a truly household name.The Bad:-Optimization: Day 1 The game has clearly not been optimized very well, if you're on a lower end machine you need to turn off anti-aliasing, action camera and  vsync in order to temporarily boost performance until they come out with a performance patch.-Difficulty: In my opinion, the difficulty for newer members of the franchise might very well be too much. While it's amusing seeing Youtubers and Streamers bash their heads into full cover Advent. I think that Firaxis might have actually made Easy / Normal a little too difficult for the people that actually need the assistance. There is also a distinct lack of 'Second-Wave' options at the outset which is a little disappointing. Seeing these added at a later date to more accurately tune difficulty to one's skill level is a good idea.-There is no mouse panning on the edges of the screen in the geoscape which is a little annoying. I might just be incredibly stupid, but that's the way it appears to be.The meh:=Graphics: While there are some noticeable graphical upgrades, it's otherwise in line with most other games out there at this time.=Multiplayer: (Pending, I have not tried it yet, I assume that it's playable as there are people playing it right now)=Timers: While I personally do not mind this too much, there seems to be a massive abundance of timed missions. This adds a significant time pressure that disrupts the old-meta of advancing from cover to cover overwatching all the time. While that playstyle is certainly still viable, there are penalties to pay for it.The Good:+Game Mechanics: Graphics are all well and good for advertising a game, but ultimately it comes down game mechanics on whether or not a game is good or even fun. Firaxis is a studio that has always prided themselves on their game design, and it is on display here. The changes they've made to Overwatch not shooting all one target, class overhauls, strategy layer improvements, concealment system, etc. All of this culminates in an experience that is truly expeptional.+Character customization: It's too much. I honestly feel like I'm playing 'The Sims' with an expansion pack that features gigantic hulking monsters that want to kill you horribly. Well, maybe sometimes... You could literally spend hours on customizing your troops by itself.+The narrative: If I could sum up the story so far in one word it would be 'compelling', while the storyline of XCOM games to date has been bare bones. This is a remarkable attempt to marry emergent stories with a plausible narrative. While the canon is certainly not for everyone, I appreciate their efforts.+Modding: While there is a limited selection of Day 1 mods, I honestly cannot wait for what the community has in store in the future. The toolkit looks to be nothing short of incredible.+Maps: Nothing short of awe-inspiring with what they've done with the procedurally generated maps. In XCOM:EU if you played the game for any significant amount of time (100h+) then you would repeat the same maps over and over again. Which ultimately made the game a chore and even worse, familiar. For all the maps there became a rote approach that was better than anything else that was naturally adopted by the players. XCOM 2 fixes those problems by giving the player  no repeat maps. Which keeps the tactical fights new and engaging every time.Conclusion:I feel that XCOM 2 is what XCOM:EU was trying to be, but ultimately was held back by missteps in the design process and a distinct lack of de-risking in this genre at the time. This ultimately lead to the developers giving the players a very canned experience and being overly cautious with how they revived and presented the XCOM brand.With that said, I wholeheartedly endorse XCOM 2. I would not be surprised that I rack up 400-500h over the next couple of months. With the line up of DLC in the pipeline and the robust modding toolkit available. I simply cannot wait for what Firaxis and the Community has in store.The only serious problems that needs to be immediately addressed is that the performance issues that range from merely annoying to fairly significant. Aside from that... A must buy for any XCOM fan!Good luck commander!Final Rating: 9.5 / 10 - Missing shots at 95% to-hits is always fun."
76561198030717155,Recommended,268500,21631876,"Posted: 4 March, 2016",all,brad.miller,"It's so sad to see one of my favorite games turned into this. XCOM2 does shine in a few areas, but overall comes across as trying far too hard to recreate the difficulty of the original XCOM series, only to feel forced and disingenuous in doing so.It confuses the player with a flaky interface, it's unpredictable with erratic visibility mechanics, and generally feels wildly inconsistent when it comes to its own in-game rules. I'm not against difficult games, but XCOM2 goes well beyond believability and enjoyability in order to create situations that simply require multiple attempts to get right. The resulting game experience is one where you feel like you're fighting against the developers instead of the in-game enemy.Edit:I said at the beginning that this game shines in some areas, and it deserves to have those pointed out. Like XCOM (both the original and the new remake), XCOM2 creates some amazing, fist-pumping moments of joy and awesomeness. The graphics are generally great, the storyline is interesting and compelling, and the core game mechanics are solid and just plain fun.So it's quite frustrating that there these moments of inconsistency, like mentioned above, that force me to reload every other turn. I get that XCOM should be a brutal game, but that brutality should come from in-game experiences within the player's expectations, not from an interface glitch, broken line of sight on grenade launchers, or the fact that I can't tell if my character can shoot from a particular position before moving him/her there.Clarified recommendation: I recommed it, but only if you're ready for a very frustrating experience."
