76561197979184781,Recommended,268500,34508286,Posted: 26 August,all,GammaKitsune,"You might see some people criticising this game for putting a timer on many of the missions.Don't listen to these people.The timer mechanic is one of the best additions to the series that Firaxis could have made. In previous X-Com titles, your were encoraged to creep through every level at a snail's pace, moving very slowly and taking turn after turn to try to get the drop on enemy aliens. This lead to a slow, dull playstyle, with lots of wasted turns and a whole lot of nothing happening. XCOM 2 makes this effectively impossible, forcing you to think on your feet, make bold strategic decisions, and sometimes fight your way out of a bad sitution that you couldn't possibly have forseen.This adds a lot of pressure and intensity to every match that just wasn't present in previous titles. Before, if you got into a bad situation it was usually because you weren't slow and overcautious enough. There was almost never a reason not to play that way. In this game there's a fine balance between playing carefully and aggressive, risky choices, because if you take it too slow you're going to run out of time and lose the mission.Besides, after you play a few rounds, you realize that they usually give you just enough time to finish. It's not that hard."
