76561198072368277,Recommended,268500,24016735,"Posted: 2 July, 2016",all,schulz1,"I think this game is an outstanding improvement over enemy unknown. I'm not terribly great at reviews, so I'll summerize my thoughts on the game in itemized form.1) Combat is more interesting: I feel like the amount of abilities the enemies possess is much more diverse and so makes for more tactical decisions in deciding how to engage.2) Soldier classes much more balanced: In enemy unknown, some of the classes just didn't hit the powercurve properly. Support was generally meh, snipers were generally OP past squaddie, etc. etc. Now it seems that there is no single class I groan about my rookies becoming because they all serve incredibly useful purposes (though rangers and grenadiers are preferable in the extremely early game).3) As in the first one, ""perfect play"" is rewarded. I can generally get through the first 8 missions or so without the enemy getting off a single shot. As enemy HP increases, this becomes more difficult, but good play will rarely leave your soldiers in mortal danger.4) The power-curve is very well balanced. Even on a blind playthrough on normal difficulty, I never felt like I was impossibly behind the aliens (but I also had very good play and only needed to recruit one soldier, that probably helped, haha!). This kind of dissappointed me, but I guess I can crank up the difficulty. New species are encountered one a fairly regular basis, each one upping the ante, but until the mid-game/end such sightings will rarely perturb the balance of power.5) XCOM development is somewhat less linear. Once the proving grounds is built, one may devote resources to new ammo, armors, grenades, etc. I enjoyed being able to choose what new items were being developed and it helps shape playstyle.The bad:1) Timed missions CAN be tedious. Some of the new missions are timed, i.e. you have x number of turns to accomplish the objective and evac. This will sometimes prove incredibly difficult to manage. I enjoy the fast past, but ironman players should be aware that many timed missions will force an uncomfortable push forward with the tradeoff typically being massive mission rewards.2) At higher levels, missions start to come in very quickly. From a gamplay perspective, this is fine as it forces either a large soldier pool or skilled play, but from a human perspective sometimes I burn out from missions and just want to watch XCOM progress their tech a little. This issue is covered more extensively in other reviews, and it is a legitimate concern, but nothing to warrent a negative review in my opinion.In summary, I think this is a fantastic tactical game. It is not without its flaws, but they are generally minor and have yet to detract from my enjoyment thus far. I had read reviews complaining of how it was unstable, contained glitches, or was unfair, but I have not encountered any of these issues."
