76561197964719677,Recommended,268500,20990470,"Posted: 6 February, 2016",all,Azrus,"Oh man, I sure missed you XCOM.So far I'm having a blast.  The on the default difficulty, game's definitely more difficult than vanilla XCOM, but not as rough as Long War was.  If you never played Long War, then you're probably going to need to adjust your tactics as you just can't get away with a lot of the risks you could take in vanilla XCOM.  Performance isn't great, though 90% of my performance issues are with the loading screen animations and navigating the base.  Combat has been pretty smooth, though there is the occasional brief pause as the aliens decide what to do.  I noticed the pause in my first battle, but hardly notice it now, so it's definitely not as big of a deal for me as it seems to be for many of the other reviewers.  My only real complaint is with the lack of the Second Wave options from the original.  I really miss guaranteed flank crits, and randomized stats/abilities.  Hopefully those will get implemented at some point.So, I definitely recommend the game.  Just understand what you're getting into.  It is undeniably more difficult than XCOM.  If you've never played XCOM, then just expect that you're going to die a lot while you learn the game.Finally, a couple of friendly tips:-Learn to flank and protect your flank.  Don't cluster your soldiers, spread them out a bit.  Try to flank along one side, use your other soldiers to keep the aliens occupied.  You want to position your soldiers so that you can approach an enemy from two directions at once.  Don't move to cover if an alien will be able to safely flank you in a single move.  If they can do that, position a second soldier so that they'll be covering the first soldier's flank.  Most of the enemies you face won't move into a square if it will result in them being flanked, use that to control the battlefield.-Overwatch.  There are very few cases you should fire at an alien if you've only got a 50% chance to hit.  Instead, stick them in overwatch.  It's a good way to discourage aliens from rushing you.  If you don't have a good shot, move up a soldier or two so that they'll be in a good position to flank on the next turn, then stick the rest on overwatch.-Leap frog with overwatch.  If you think the enemy is close or you've lost concealment, then you want to try to keep half your team on overwatch while you move.  Rushing the entire team up by sprinting is a great way to get massacred.-Movement is much safer while concealed.  If you need to cover a lot of ground quickly, try to maintain concealement or bring along Rangers.-Just because you can kill everyone, doesn't mean you should.  Missions with turn limits are a lot easier if you focus on the objective.  Try to maintain concealment for as long as possible and move quickly.  Rooftops tend to be safer than the streets and they'll give you a better vantage point so you can keep track of patrols.  If you want to stick around and kill some aliens, then it's best to get the objective first and fight near your evac point.-Bring two medkits.  Losing your medic three turns into a battle really sucks.  Having another medkit, even if it's on your Ranger or Grendadier can make life a lot easier.-Retaliation missions can be a lot easier if you bring along a Ranger that can grant themselves concealment.  Run them ahead of your team to grab the civilians you need to secure the win.  With any luck, you won't walk into a Faceless.  Try not to spot too many alien pods at once.  They kill less civilians before they get spotted.-Finally, try not to push too far into the fog of war if you're already in a fight.  Fights become a lot harder if you accidentally push up and spot a second pod of aliens.  Take your time, life is a lot easier when numbers are on your side.Anyway, I think it's a great game and I think anyone who's interested in a challenging turn based strategy game will really enjoy it."
