,Recommended,268500,20988876,"Posted: 5 February, 2016",all,The Merovingian,"First going to address a lot of the gripes about the game since I believe people are being a bit unfair. XCOM 2 has done a fantastic job of adding new content to a already great game and added a challenge to it akin to Darkest Dungeon.--Mission time limits--These are NOT unfair. People are complaining that a 8 turn limit mission is crap and there are too many of them. Out of 20 missions about 60% of them were 8 turn limits. The rest were either 12 limit or unlimited. The 8 turns were kinda nasty to be honest but they were doable. You just have to learn how to move. You can't act like it's XCOM Enemies Within anymore and just pop pods without there being severe consequences. You have to get it done in a shorter period of time which makes the game more difficult, but also far more fun. I will admit it's probably not for the casual gamer but mods might be good if you find it to be too much of a hinderance.--Accuracy seems too low--It adds a degree of challenge now so you can't just turn everyone into a sniper. At times this felt a little unfair until I realized that I was wrong. You can optimize your aim by taking high ground and strategizing and it's definitely a return to form as a lot of the earlier XCOM's were like that. This just makes you work a little more for each attack phase to be as potent as you need it to be.--Bugs galore! (Not really...)--I've heard people say there are terrible framerate issues but I haven't seen them yet. I've seen people saying that there are super long delays in moves and THIS I have seen, but it's not game breaking, and I'm being lenient towards the complainers here because I have my games installed on a solid state drive so I might have a TAD more speed during these moments. I've also heard numerous stories of crashes and have even seen this on Angry Joe's review but in the 15 hours I've got so far I haven't had a single crash. I've also heard people complaining about black screens on enemy movements and I only saw this once out of 20 missions and nothing really special happened.  Beyond those three things I haven't seen a single other bug at all and I wouldn't be surprised if a lot of those were hot patched soon.--Pistols are only used by sharpshooters???--I can't believe the amount of whining I've seen on THIS. I mean... I understand how you USED to use the pistols but to be perfectly honest, there is no reason for everyone to have a pistol in XCOM2. With the other added mechanics you really don't need it. The devs made it that way for a reason and that reason is because they were resource sinks that no one truly benefitted from to justify the cost. Glad it's gone. I might have missed something on the last XCOM game where pistols were just the bees knees but I'll be darned if I see it.Now for the actual review: Game's great. Far more challenging than its predecessor but that is something I've really wanted anyway. Is it worth the triple A price? Yeah, definitely. Bugs will be worked out, the modding community will continue to release awesome conversions, and future content will be out soon enough.So the elephant in the room... The season pass... That's debatable since we have no way of knowing at the time of this review what that will entail. 20 dollars for the content is actually a nice price point and if they follow the path they did back with XCOM EU and EW then it's possible that the content being released will be well worth it. To be honest no one knows. It's mostly speculation. It's entirely up to the buyer to decide but from this humble perspective I really can't see the harm in going the full 20 dollars in at this point yet I could respect someones decision to wait because DLC and season passes left a bad taste in a lot of gamers mouths as of recently.EDIT***** 2/23/2016First review above was with about 15 to 20 hours of gameplay. This is with considerably more.After throwing in far more time I've noticed two bugs that aren't huge. First is just a camera bug where it sometimes cuts to nothing or cuts to the inside of a building and you don't see any action. This happened a couple times and isn't gamebreaking. Other bug is just a simple animation jerk which might just be my PCs fault. I still have not seen a single crash, if this was hot patched I really didn't notice or read into it.Procedurally generated levels are keeping it fresh. Only campaign scripted missions remain constant as far as I can see.Game feels a tad linear in that choosing what to build inevitably ends the same if you have any hope of keeping the avatar project at bay. Same thing with choosing what to develop first as far as research goes. Not game breaking but a little disappointing. Could be fixed with a simple mod but I'd rather see them patch a fix in. Just something to make building things a little less important for early game so folks can try to do things differently with less negative results; IE campaign ending decision because you build a psi lab instead of a comm relay or something.I still maintain my position on the pistol, accuracy, and timed mission points. I think all of those were good decisions to give this game it's own flavor and challenge.Game still worth a buy at full price for sure."
