76561198048404706,Recommended,268500,20987099,"Posted: 5 February, 2016",all,Inosinate,"Edit:  There is now a mod available in the workshop that disables the timers, so whether or not the timers are ""bad"" is now a non issue.  Try the game, if you don't like the timers, install the mod and disable them and play to your preference.  Yay for mod support letting us choose how we play the game :)----------------------------------------------------------After reading some of the reviews on here, I got very worried about the ""turn timers"" everyone is warning about.  But now that I've played the game a bit, I felt like writing this review to say that *in my opinion at least*, they really aren't that bad.  I've actually enjoyed them.I'm really not a fan of turn timers, and the bomb missions were my least favorite of the first game.  So I definitely understand people's frustration with them.  I do think it would be a good idea for an option to disable/limit them to be added to the game.That being said, these negative reviews act as though it's somehow game breaking and removes the opportunity to use tactics.  In my experience so far this is simply not true.  None of the timed missions made me feel particularly rushed.  I didn't have to dash across the entire map.  I could take my time moving from cover to cover; I just had to have a sense of urgency and make sure I was moving TOWARDS my objective each turn and not away from it.  No turtle crawling step by step.Most of the timed missions simply require you to REACH an objective before the timer runs out, and then you can take your sweet time clearing the map of the remaining hostiles.  There's usually plenty of time to get there.  You just have to keep an eye on where that objective is as you plan your moves in the game to make sure you're progressing towards it.I think people are frustrated that there are so many timed missions (understandably) and are exaggerating how bad they are a little bit as a result of that frustration.  Or they just had some terrible luck (happens sometimes in this kind of game) and it made the game feel unfairly hard; if a bunch of enemy encounters are triggered in quick succession at the wrong time it can make turn timed missions nearly impossible.  And I can see how these situations can leave a bad taste in people's mouths.  But that is the nature of an XCOM game; sometimes things just go wrong.  If you don't have a high tolerance for that then this game will definitely frustrate you sometimes.  The game can definitely be unfair, maybe even more so than the first, and you will either love it or hate it.So, in summary,  if you absolutely can't stand the idea of timed missions you may wish to wait to buy this until after an option to disable them is added by the devs or modding community, however if you are on the fence about it then I would recommend that you don't let all the negative reviews scare you away and go ahead and try the game for yourself."
