76561198043017668,Not Recommended,268500,34134434,Posted: 9 August,all,Midnight,"So, XCOM 2 is not a bad game on its own. The reason why I find myself not being able recommend it to most people is because it is just so much like enemy unknown without really adding all that much that is really new, and even loosing some things from the previous game, while still being a full $60 more than a year after launch. I feel like a lot of people gave this game a free pass and I really dont think they should have.The four new classes are really the same from enemy unkown except with the skill tree reanged and a few new skills. Ranger is assault but with a sword (which has a higher chance to miss than it probably should and can be stopped and countered by some enemy types - so i never find myself using it very often because i dont like having to find a new ranger every mission), Specialist is Support but has a drone, Sharpshooter is sniper but with a pistol and some skills for said pistol, and grenadier is heavy but with a grenade launcher isntead of a rocket launcher. The only big difference for classes is the psi trooper, which is now its own class instead of being something added on to one of the existing classes.The theme of being a resistance and setting up ambushes is largely wasted in most of the actual gameplay. The stealth mechanic - concealment - only lasts until you are first detected/ attack an enemy, at which point your whole squad is revealed for the rest of the mission (with the exception of ranger if you take one of two skills, but you do turn down some good options for it so i rarely ever did). so, you get to set up an ambush - at best - once a mission. its also a bit easy to get revealed before setting up your ambush. In addition most missions have to be completed within x amount of turns, which means you dont get much time to perfectly set things up, or scout around to see what exactly you are up against. It ends up feeling like the whole stealth mechanic is largely wasted and doesnt really add anything.After that there isnt really much added to this game from Enemy Unkown to really make it its own thing. It feels almost like a mod of Enemy Unkown with better visuals. It actually takes some things away. for example meld is no longer a thing along with the things that went with it, and even things like the second wave options are gone.To add to it, the game doesnt run well. Despite Firaxis stating they were focusing just on the PC to make it as good as possible (although they ended up porting it to consoles later) it feels like a bad port from console. From how the camera works to controls the game often feels too clunky to be something designed for a mouse and keyboard, and this is the only game I have that will repeatedly crash. I also get a lot of big frame drops, animations breaking, and the occasional loading screen that randomly goes on for ages.Now that all being said, if you are the type of gamer that likes to be put against insane odds which you will most likely not win but like to see how far you can get, you should probably ignore everything i just said and buy it. from my experience XCOM2 is significantly more difficult than Enemy Unkown, adding in enemy types with some crazy stats and abilities - a lot of which in the right situation will just feel flat out unfair. higher rank soldiers are capable of a lot more damage output than previously, but as soon as they are out injured or killed and you are back to lower/middle ranked soldiers you'll likely start having a lot of people die. Also the avenger deffence mission (which it seems like you will always get this at least once in a playthrough assuming you dont get wiped out first) is crazy levels of difficult, which on higher difficulties can end up with you lossing a significant amount of your roster in one mission. It also feels like chances to hit (for the player, anyway) are largely lower across the board than Enemy Unkown. particularly with overwatch, which feels like the chance for them to hit is so low there is almost not even a point to using it - or i have just been insanely unlucky. It also feels like the enemy knows you'll miss too, not hesitating to run straight through it - seemingly knowing all of your soldiers are about to miss despite being six feet away.Overall I cant really recommend this to the typical player. To me it falls short for smillar reasons that Civ Beyond Earth fell short. If the price drops or if there is a sale with the DLC it could be worth picking up, but as it is unless you just really want more xcom i cant really recommend it."
