76561197971285241,Not Recommended,268500,21286101,"Posted: 17 February, 2016",all,Meowmeow,"I really wanted to be able to give a positive review for this game since I’ve been a fan of the X-com series since I was a kid. However, after playing through veteran and beating the game, and getting partially through commander I have to admit I didn't really enjoy the game as I had hoped.I'll start with the most frustrating part of the game. The hit percentages. Granted this is a problem that has carried over from Enemy Unknown but, it seems to have gotten much worse. This is not due to bad luck since I have tried to get my soldiers in different positions to attack an enemy and it doesn't matter if you have a 50% chance to hit or 90% chance to hit. If the AI has decided that soldier will miss on a certain target there's nothing you can do except try to attack a different target, load your game and try a different approach or be content with missing and losing a Major. This is not offering a ""challenge"", it is intentionally altering your chances so that you will miss now and then. This is supposed to be a strategy game. the decisions you make should not be affected by an AI that randomly decides to make you miss. It would be like playing chess and your opponent decides to randomly punt your pawns off the board. This follows into my next peeve.The game is now half based on strategical placement. With the Codex and Avatar being able to teleport right behind your cover or the Snakeman able to grab you from 8 squares away at full cover or the Archon that just flies from a mile away and gets a critical head bash dealing 12 damage in one shot, the idea that this game is based on strategical advantages is laughable. The sharpshooters are still a great soldier to use and for that I am thankful.The whole game is rushed. And I don't mean rushed through development (even though that is most likely the case.) The game forces you to make brash hurried decisions in 2 ways: the Avatar project on the main geoscape that will ultimately decide you will lose if you take too long accomplishing the main questline. If you make mistakes early on and decide to let that Avatar counter get to high your game will certainly be a failure and you will need to restart (my first game.) I wasn't even able to get through the tech tree or get a maxed out psionic warrior on my first victory because of that. The other rushed aspect is the turn counter in battle. It's rare when I can get a mission to 5+ turns before utter failure. Again this is another aspect where you will have to start over if you made any mistake in the beginning.They also ditched a lot of the aspects of the game i loved. In XCOM 1,2 and EU you had a heavy weapons platform you could bring with you in place of a squad member. It was nice having those since it didn’t gain experience and could be replicated I didn’t mind it being blown up in combat and I took a much more aggressive battle strategy using them. Also, no more vehicle creation? One of the greatest aspects of the game was making your own flying saucer after a lengthy time in the research tree. Besides all that, there are plenty of bugs to find but, that is pretty normal for games that are shipped out prior to being completed nowadays.On the brighter side of things the game offers a lot of new tech including being able to hack robotic enemies and a variety of grenades and ammunition variants that give a great amount of versatility when creating a squad (love the grenadiers in an exo-suit.) The plot line is well developed and intriguing. The addition of customizable weapons per squadmate as well as the PCS units was a nice addition but you may not get the drops you want in your limited time window.All in all i tried to rate the game based on how much I enjoyed it and I would give it 2/5 the sheer frustration of the mechanics in this game has gotten me to abandon it and would not recommend this to a friend as I would not want them to feel the same."
