76561197970329457,Not Recommended,268500,22385604,"Posted: 12 April, 2016",all,Al Paradise,"Big fan of the premise. This is probably as close as we'll get to ID4: The Game. The problem isn't the concept, it's the execution.Ultimately, if you want just a carbon copy of XCOM1's gameplay elements -- top-down view, 2 moves per soldier, etc. -- then you'll love this game. If you want some innovative design ideas and a gripping story, you need to look elsewhere.They somehow managed to make the story even more boring and shallow than in XCOM1, which is particularly evident as you dig deeper. Once you get past all the mystic mumbo jumbo garbage, it's a bunch of nothing under the guise of ambiguity. I would've preferred a giant, glowing brain-in-a-jar kicking in humanity's front door to steal all their water or whatever than what XCOM2 hands you. At least the brain thing would've been fun.Gameplay is more of the same except now it's ""resistance"" flavor. Which is fine because XCOM1's chess match style gameplay was great. Except that there's a new concealment 'feature.' There's no explanation or tutorial on how to best use this. Initially, I thought you could complete objectives and missions concealed, then disappear into the shadows. That's not the case. If you don't attack the first group of enemies you see, you eventually reveal all the enemy groups the deeper you go into the map. When you reach the objective, there are permanently stationed enemies around it. By then revealing yourself, you activate each group of enemies until you're surrounded.It's a waste of a great concept. Stealthy resistance tactics diluted down to a free overwatch shot.Character customization options are a little bit better in places but also worse in places than the previous game. Most facial hair looks terrible, and there simply aren't that many options. They managed to add a few more accents -- such as British and Australian English -- but removed other languages entirely, which is a shame.tl;dr: Great concept, terrible execution. Regret blowing $60 on this, probably worth more like $20-30."
