76561197983877129,Not Recommended,268500,21312779,"Posted: 18 February, 2016",all,slipperyfrog,"Its rare I play a game that I love, and hate so much at the same time as Xcom 2. The game is a non stop barrage of highs and pittfalls. There is a strange duality of quality in every facet of this game, that I have rarely seen outside of an indie game. The game looks and plays exactly the same as ""Enemy Unknown"" and somehow is even plagued by many of the exact same graphical, an UI issues that dragged down its predecessor. The game has grown little since its last itteration, and many of the new mechanics the game prides itself on, are so poorly fleshed out as not to add anything meanful to the experience. While there have been a number of improvements to the balance of the gameplay, the game can't seem to decide if it wants to hold your hand, or throw you to the wolves. All too often I found myself muttering ""Yeah... I get it."" or to the other extreme of ""Where was the explination for that?"" There is a lot going on in this game, with a whole slew of things to juggle if you are to succeed, and a strangley heavy handed, or an altogether detramentally late explination of many of the new resource mechanics in play. On top of this the game has an unnecessary amount of waiting built into everything. There are pauses, and cooldown timers attached to everything from animations, menu navigations, game actions (both player and enemy), and character naration, making for a frustratingly slow progression to get to the gameplay itself. At the end of it all this is less a sequal, and more of a massive expansion to ""Enemy Unknown"" and not a terribly ambitious one. Even in lue of all of that, it is still somehow a joy to play, thanks entirely to the modding community. They have come together to fix, many of the failings and blemishes of this tittle, and turn it into something that is a load of fun. Its a tooth and nail fight uphill all the way, as you struggle for a foot hold in the face of an overwhelmingly superiour force. The satisfaction of working your way up through alien armies, with nothing but your whits to protect you is surprisingly refreshing, in an increasingly resource oriented Strategy genre.As it is, at the end of the day, I can't recommend this game without the heavy use of modding. The vanilla experience essentually a jar of jellybeans at the far end of a room of rock salt and broken glass. Yeah there is enjoyment to be had in it, but you have to suffer to get to it."
