76561197973952918,Recommended,268500,21644791,"Posted: 5 March, 2016",all,blu_light16,"As a big fan of XCOM: Enemy Unknown, I was surprised to see how many things changed with XCOM 2. Along with the new futuristic setting, almost every aspect of the gameplay has been tweaked or modified in some significant way; altogether, it makes XCOM 2 feel wholly fresh and unique – even if not all of the changes are for the better.What stood out the most early on was the steep learning curve; it wasn't until around the 30-hour mark that I felt like I had a good understanding of how things worked. The “Veteran” difficulty setting struck me as being WAY too hard for a first playthrough. I recommend setting it to the easiest mode, at least for the first bunch of hours.Of course, the complexity that makes it hard to warm up to is part of what fuels its replay value – there is an enormous amount of depth here. You can modify soldier weapons and some of their stats with special items, equip different kinds of armor, manage research projects and constructions, keep track of limited supplies, manage special development projects and special reseach projects......umm, actually there are TOO many things to keep track of. It reminds me of the excessive micromanagement of the first Mass Effect – the depth is definitely there, but it takes too long to get anything done.The weakest part of XCOM 2 is the story. It comes across as rather cliché average sci-fi, but at least has a very strong presentation with stylish cutscenes and good voice acting. Visually, the whole game feels “brighter” than Enemy Unknown, but still has the same great use of color and special effects. It's a lot of fun to take screenshots during the cinematic moments in battle – give it a try!It's easy to compare XCOM 2 to Enemy Unknown and point out its flaws, but at the end of the day the turn-based strategy battles and base-management elements have a similar kind of engaging, almost compulsive appeal with very high replay value. It is intense, entertaining, and will push your intellect to the limit. Just be sure to treat this game the way you would any hostile alien: approach with caution.(Rating: 9/10 “Great”)"
76561198118413514,Recommended,268500,20963122,"Posted: 4 February, 2016",all,viddamao,awesome graphics and game play. lots of new stuff even if u finished xcom already.
76561198060101030,Recommended,268500,21023084,"Posted: 7 February, 2016",all,DickoTheMLGPro,"I've only played about 3 hrs, and so far i haven't had any game breaking bugs, crashes etc. So I'm pretty stoked with the game and can see myself putting quite a few hours into this.8/8 MATE"
76561197962100857,Recommended,268500,21013946,"Posted: 6 February, 2016",all,six-P-,"You will either love or hate this game. The timer mechanic is fantastic if you like gritty missions where failure and complete squad loss occurs (best played with Ironman). If you liked to go through every mission near-flawlessly and perfectly level up your squad and seldom lose soldiers or missions, you probably won't like X-COM 2. It's tone is substantially changed from the first one due to the inclusion of the timer mechanic. Or you can save your soilders by aborting the mission, which is my current go-to option. The gritty pace extends to base management and the global map, and in terms of that, I'm much more lukewarm, because it almost requires you to play the game multiple times to know the importance of timing of plot events. But that kind of existed in X-COM 1 as well - i.e. the base attack.On the downside, the graphics are basically the same as X-COM 1 (trivial improvements) and the performance is much worse, probably because of some random default graphics setting that I haven't yet tried to tweak. Edit: I tried tweaking a few settings, and the game still stutters on a i7-6700k@4.5Ghz, 980gtx, 16gb ram, ssd. There are also a few graphical glitches and a few minor but noticeable bugs here and there. Definitely less polished than earlier releases.Still, a great game. Oh, and a word of advice: Don't be afriad to call in an emergency evac - despite the mission objectives - sometimes is necessary to overcome spikes in difficulty due to random generation of terrain and alien patrols. Overall, I'd rank this game as better than Enemy Unknown, but somewhat less than Enemy Within."
