76561198024963796,Not Recommended,268500,28315987,"Posted: 11 December, 2016",all,(oWo) Samael11,"So I just beat XCOM 2 recently.Second serious attempt.Ironman Commander.And the more I think about it, the less I can recommend this game to everyone in general, especially at 50-60$.I don't recall if I played the Enemy Within/Unknown on Impossible, but I know I didn't Ironman it, so this one seems easier from the start, at least when it doesn't outright cheat.Unless you go Legend difficulty, then the game gets real hard real quick (Like, the very first mission has twice as many enemies and you are running in to sectoids like 5 missions earlier than you should).Overall it's solid and remains one of the best turn-based tactical games on the market, but it has its fair share of flaws, annoyances and bugs.But before reading further, know that it is overall an enjoyable game if you like the genre, and I recommend checking it out if you liked Enemy Within / Unknown, especially if it's on sale for 20 or 30$.Just be prepared for some bullpoop.If you didn't play the previous game, I'd suggest checking that one out first, since it's less expensive and probably more enjoyable and stable.Getting into why I can't recommend this game to people not already interested / invested in the recent XCOM franchise...The last 2 or 3 cinematics would freeze the video (though audio was fine, and the game would advance) and the last mission crashed on me once.  Nothing major, a minor annoyance, but the cinematic is youtube-able, and the crash didn't wipe my data, so I'm not upset about that.The DLC is fun but lacks clarity.The content is great, but if you don't know what the DLC missions are, and that they are the only missions that are not time-sensitive, they can end your ironman run when they pop up, especially if it's your first game of XCOM 2 - which happened to me.They are balanced well enough for an early game party, until you get to the last fight, when it's nothing but unbalanced bullpoo.  Having a squad of 3 +2 special NPCs, all with lowest-tier gear go up against a sectopod is what ended my first ironman run, and I had an even better start then the one I completed the game with (there was some cheating targeting bull that didn't help too, see the next 2 issues).One of the more uncommon bugs I ran into that is potentially game-breaking in an ironman run is enemies having vision and LoS through walls.Yes windows and doors exist and most walls can be shot through and destroyed, but some structures are invulnerable and windowless, and when the enemy can see and shoot you through those walls and you are unable plan for that or even return fire, that is plain cheating and can cause you to lose squad members.  I had one Viper shoot a poison cloud through an indestructable wall that poisoned 4 of my squaddies and a VIP pretty early in the game.On a related note, on missions where additional enemies are added to a fight (which is many of them), they are allowed an immediate move, but not an action.Which is fine.  But they are added to a fight, and move, as the first part of the enemy turn, before the existing enemies you made your tactical decisions for, have their action.  So all those guys you have on overwatch covering themselves, or an overextended squadmate, against the low health hostile aiming his shot, will be wasted on enemies that are not an immediate threat to your squad, and you will lose squadmates to that issue.Certain ability usage uses a completely different input scheme than the most common inputs, so it is very likely when you are looking to pick a different target, or change targeting, you will give a command for a character to run in and take a melee swing, or other action, you did not intend to take.  VERY dangerous on ironman runs.Wounds seem arbitrary.I've had squaddies with 15+ health finish a mission having taken only 2 points of damage and needing to sit out 15 days to heal, while squadmates on the same missions with 13 health finish 2 pips left and are ready to go again in 3-5 days.Pacing is weird (I didn't like it)Almost every mission is time-limited (to one or two days) and super-mandatory to attempt (and succeed at).There's no balance of ""Is this mission worth it?  Do I really need the reward it gives?"" and letting the player take a moment to not have to do a mission immediately and finish his upgrade that needs half a day to complete.And the time spent in the overworld researching and contacting countries and building is shorter than it should be in between those missions.Early game shortly after you start scanning something, you will have to take care of a mission.  And it only gets worse in the mid-game.You can't enjoy the fruits of your labor as much, since you have to sit there putting out 5 missions worth of fires before you can finally finish anything and start new research (which you have to do to advance the story).What's more, if you have a good start, you can research end-game weapons before you're even in the mid-game.  But if you have a bad start, you are missing so much that you can never catch up as the mission failures start cascading hard.The end game conversely has almost no missions pop up, so if you need something you are sitting at HQ scanning for it.  And considering how rare Elerium cores can be, if you need to farm a few, you're going to be waiting a long time.  (Though you should probably have just enough to cover needs by end game, thankfully).The pricing of Crew members via HQ is prohibitive until mid game and impractical until end game.Supplies are immensely valuable, and needing to drop 100+ on a scientist, engineer or squad member is a waste early game when you actually need them, but can't afford them and need to upgrade your gear.  Especially when, for 80 intel you can get them from the black market (though that is somewhat of a waste too, but less of one).The variety of mission styles is woefully small.  It's adequate enough, but misses out on some good opportunities.Basically the missions you will run into are:-Protect something-Extract the VIP-Blow something up-Hack Something-Protect the resistance base personnelThat's it.  And most of those missions have the secondary objective of ""Kill all hostiles"" for a proper reward.On top of that, due to the way concealment and vision works in the game along with the prcedural generation of maps (which is alright but not that special), the few missions where you don't have to kill everything, don't encourage smaller squads or allow for stealth missions or assassination missions or a multitude of better designed missions, so you end up killing everything anyway."
76561197978142103,Not Recommended,268500,28314473,"Posted: 11 December, 2016",all,Dogmatius,"Alright.. So a while back I wrote a drunken angry review that wasn't really helpful at all and I figured it was about time to write a new one. It will still be negative, but this time I'll do my best to explain why.It's a strange love & hate relationship with XCOM2. While I do enjoy it and find it to be one of my favorite isometric tactical shooters out there, I still despise it. To a degree that turns my gut inside out. Confused..? Well maybe a metaphor will help describe it better.. XCOM2 is like perfect aged single malt whisky. It's an acquired taste not for everyone. Best enjoyed by pouring a single glass, roll it around in your hand, let the aroma fill your nostrils and then slowly enjoy it a sip at the time. But drink the whole bottle at once and you'll end up annoyed, confused and ready to puke your guts out.Guess what I'm trying to say is that XCOM2 is great if you take the time to enjoy the small ""sips"" like extensive soldier customization, resource management, base building, huge destructible maps and a amazing level of detail. If you're not and just looking for quick ""buzz"" of tactical turn based combat, then you'll get choked up before you're halfway through. Mostly by bugs, glitches, poor difficulty scaling and a bs RNG system that leaves most people save-scumming their way through the campaign. Bottom line, if you don't enjoy all the small things then this game will be nothing but a headache.If that weren't enough, there's still bugs in the game that has been there since its initial release. The community have long ago identified and found solutions to most of these problems and yet Firaxis Games has done nothing to fix it. In a recent post a developer even claimed they're still watching the forums for feedback, but what good is that if they just ignore the problems at hand. I simply can't recommend a game where the developers leave it to the modders to fix their problems.So is this the only reason I'll give it a negative review..? No. I'll give it a negative review because it's a game for hardcore fans of tactical turnbased games, but the difficulty and gamemode meant for them (legend ironman) is the buggiest of all. And everything below Legend difficulty is way to easy for experienced players in this genre. Avarage Joe might get some fun out of it if he's prepared to do a little research and load a few mods to adjust and fix his game. So unless you're really into this genre it ain't worth the price. 20€ at most in my opinion, since it's something most people would proberly play and forget.For my opinion on the individual DLC packs available, read my review for each one of them."
