76561198032515759,Recommended,268500,21074398,"Posted: 9 February, 2016",all,bzavitsky,"Xcom is NOT a game for everyone. Xcom is designed in such a way as to test your ability to stay calm and collected in the face of adversity, and sometimes, extreme loses. Unless playing on ""easy"" or ""normal"", losing squad members and even missions IS THE WAY XCOM PLAYS.I've played Xcom Enemy Unknown (and LongWar) for over 280hrs. What draws me to this turned based tactical shooter is the challenge, the frustration, followed by the (eventual) exhilaration of succeeding. Personally, I'm not impressed by games that are 95% eye candy with only 5% challenge... Games that the path to victory is all but guaranteed. I want a game that pushes me to my limits and, right when I think I cannot take it anymore, draws me back in due to interesting and dynamic game mechanics that makes me think ""just one more mission"" or, after failing the campaign and restarting for the 4th time, ""just one more try, let me try some other tactics"".Xcom 2 is in my mind the ultimate turned based strategy with NO equal, either in the past or contemporary. You have procedurally generated maps, randomized missions, a refreshing variety of mission types, greatly improved AI, significantly improved story, large tech tree to explore, more balanced classes with interesting skills to choose from, and lots of tactical possibilities to name but a few. The cherry on top of the cake: The game itself (unlike Xcom EW/EU) is very mod friendly = unlimited future possibilities, playability, and customization.To be fair, there are some cons. First, performance in Xcom 2 is not super responsive. There seems to be input delays, pauses and freezes when blowing things up as well as when the enemy AI is plotting their move. Nothing that is game breaking, but it does need to be addressed and fixed. Second, the timers on both certain missions as well as the Avatar Project should be tweaked. While I like the sense of urgency, at times I also feel too rushed… Some missions are even timed so short that the only path to success is to rush it in concealment and hope you don’t run into the enemy and get surrounded and swarmed by every bad guy on the entire map! And when that happens the mission is a 99% failure with moderate to heavy casualties guaranteed. In fact, the timer mechanic has been, overall, responsible for every one of my campaign fails.In a nutshell, Xcom 2 is not for everyone… It’s certainly not for anyone who expect glass-like FPS performance with straight forward tactics and paths to victory. Xcom 2 is ultimately an extreme thinking game that FORCES you accept and manage failure and crises, while keeping the big picture in mind. While there are some issues that need to be addressed and balanced, Xcom 2 is a master piece and I suspect will go down as the ultimate turned-based cult classic."
