,Recommended,268500,21119803,"Posted: 10 February, 2016",all,Vid-szhite,"This game is incredible. A masterpiece of turn-based strategy that makes this a worthy successor even to the phenomenal XCOM: Enemy Within. Best of all, it does so without invalidating a lot of what the original XCOM does, it has its own flavor and style that lets both games coexist happily. Truly Game of the Year material....when it works.Unfortunately, even though I've got pretty great hardware, such that the game automatically pegs my hardware as being good enough for max settings, I get massive framerate drops. I'll be flying along at 60 FPS, and then the camera moves two inches and I'm chugging along at 5 FPS for several seconds. Worse yet, the in-engine cutscenes all drop to 20 FPS even with settings at minimum. Worst of all, sometimes the game locks my whole computer so bad that CTRL-ALT-DEL doesn't even work. The weird thing is, it's not consistent. Sometimes, the soldier select screen will drop to 30 FPS as soon as the soldiers are loaded, but if you turn away from it to add a mod to one of their weapons and come back, the same exact scene is now 75 FPS, even though there's MORE on the screen than before.I still recommend it because a patch to fix performance is in the works, and since it's turn-based, it's merely annoying rather than game-breaking. If you're willing to put up with the performance issues, by all means, it's worth it."
,Recommended,268500,21120221,"Posted: 10 February, 2016",all,MetalGear007,"Review with 2nd Impression:1st Impression: First review I've ever written - fitting that it should be for XCOM 2. I rarely buy games on release, I usually wait until a sale to buy games, but I shelled out $75 for the game and DLC. So far it has been worth it.As someone who has played nearly 300+ hours of XCOM: Enemy Within/Enemy Unknown, I have to recommend this game. (-Yes, the RNG will drive you crazy and if you don't like it, you won't like it now. I feel that it's always been part of XCOM and while a missed shot will♥♥♥♥♥♥you off, it shouldn't make or break the battle. Mind that I still feel like breaking my mouse when I miss a 90%...)Positives:-Customization (Plenty of more options, making your guys more unique and way cooler than the last XCOM. It's also worse when you lose someone. It still irks me when I take the time to make a soldier, only to have them get killed instantly)-Missions (The variety, the randomly generated maps, the objectives: I love all of it. Refreshing change from XCOM: EW. Some people may be annoyed with the timed missions, but I personally feel that they force action and decisiveness as a whole)-Story (Been great so far - just finished the Blacksite Mission and am really into the game. Yes, I've played 22.3 hours over the past week when I have lots of school >_>)-Modding (Long War - enough said)-Class variety (They all feel unique and have a part to play in a battle)-Time Limit (I like the real aspect of the game - ex: trying to evacuate a VIP should have a time limit as the enemy is undoubtedly hunting you. It forces less conservative play, and harder missions. However, it's not to the point where it is unbeatable.Negatives:-Yes, there are optimization problems. My computer actually runs about 10-15 FPS. Yet the game is so good in itself that I'm willing to play through it. Once an optimization patch comes out, this shouldn't be a problem.-Glitchy (Phasing through walls, melee through walls, shooting in the opposite direction and hitting the target)-Camera Angles (Will sometimes show you a view that's blocked immediately off by a wall/ceiling)Some really quick impression of the game after about 22.3 hours. Excellent game so far, and will be even better with the optimization. Improvements all around - if you liked EU or EW, buy it! 9/10 for me."
