,Recommended,268500,21132561,"Posted: 11 February, 2016",all,codexus,"XCOM: Enemy Unknown managed to successfully resurrect the XCOM series, XCOM 2 continues it brilliantly.Procedural level generation, that was an important aspect of the original XCOM, is finally back for better replayability. Also the new concealment mechanic eliminates some of the randomness of triggering the alien groups and instead allows us to plan deadly ambushes (so satisfying when they work well).One controversial point is that most missions now have an objective that must be reached within a fixed number of turns. While I was a bit surprised at first, I think this is actually very good. XCOM is all about risk management and without an incentive to go faster, the best strategy is to play extremely defensively, advancing your soldiers as little as possible each turn. With the timers, you have to balance safety vs efficiency and that makes the game a lot more dynamic and interesting.In terms of story and background, they managed to keep things fresh: XCOM is now the resistance against a well established alien presence (it seems inspired by the ""V"" TV series).One negative point is that the game feels quite glitchy (weird line of sights, bad camera angles, silly animations, bugs). That was already the case of the previous one and they never really fixed all the problems. I would have hoped that when starting fresh on a new game, they would have restarted from a more solid foundation but it looks like they just reused the old code (bugs included) for many things.Overall, I absolutely recommended this game to all XCOM fans or even people new to the series!Now if only I could get Central Officer Bradford to STFU, maybe my guys would be able to concentrate and stop missing those 99% shots ;)"
