76561198036034268,Recommended,268500,21243131,"Posted: 15 February, 2016",all,Bede,"This is the best stratagy game i've played in a long time. I never write reviews but the critism this game is recieving game play-wise is unwarrented. Rather than review I'd like to address complaints and convince those who got frustraited to give the game another shot.The performance issues are warrented, and i don't blame people for being upset.  I had some weird things happen, and the game crashed 3x during my 60hr playtime.  I wonder if operating system plays a role. I have Windows 7,  i have an average card but have lots of gpu and ram memory.  I wonder if MS W10 is causing issues.  i havent seen anyone post if this plays a role. Still For the most part i've not had many problems.Gameplay: I'm not the best Xcom 1 player, but still i started Xcom 2 on vetern the first game, suffice to say it was very frustraiting.  I restarted it on the easiest difficulty and its much much better. There is no shame in playing on this lvl, and saving and reloading when things got out of hand. Remember its Xcom its suppose to be hard, u need to learn how to play the game, once u figure things out and ""get the game"" its awesome.  You can always play through it again later on iron man.  As far as the timers they make sense ""in the context of the game"", be sure to know the mission parameters and plan accordingly.  If you go in every mission guns blazing every mission you will get into trouble.  Use stealth and ambush, save constantly, flank your opponent, get the heck out of there (u need not kill everything on certain missions) use the tools the game gives you, once you learn the game, you won't need to as much.  Also if the ai is cheap reload, if u make a big mistake reload. Keep trying till u beat the mission. I have never had an expired timer yet, the game has a learning curve.  Firaxis made a very old school difficuly type game, back in the early 90's it took weeks to figure out how to play a stratagy game.  If you give up on this game your just cheating yourself.  I'm playing on veteren and am holding my own so far. If i can do it, most of u can, just give it another chance!"
,Recommended,268500,21243416,"Posted: 15 February, 2016",all,TheFiftySeventhOfTheBootyFiends,"The game is a great new take on the XCOM series, and I enjoyed every minute of playing it. The story (in my opinion) was very engaging, and the game drew me back in every time. I wholeheartedly recommend this game. However, with every game there are some cons.STOP READING NOW IF YOU DONT WANT THE STORY SPOILED!:Many animations throughout the game are dragged out to a point where its ajust frusterating to have them there. For instance, when you find a patrol of aliens, the game will freeze on the patrol for a good 10-15 seconds before making any other actions. Another example is when you kill an alien, it freezes on the dead body for a few seconds before letting you play again. However, none of these pauses are bad enough to make you want to stop playing, just slightely frustrating. As well, if it really bothers you as much as it did me, you can install the ""Stop Wasting My Time Mod"" which will get rid of these pauses and speed certain aspects of the game up. These next few opinions are coming from a guy who played the old game extensively. The game seemed to be lacking something the whole experience and I found out what it was. Enemy Unknown had you doing almost boss fights throughout the game, which got you progressing in the story. XCOM 2 just doesnt have that, and it feels empty. Also, the old game had tons of options in the beggining that allowed for so much more replay value, however in this game, there are no options but Ironman, which doesnt allow you to load old saves, and makes all your moves permanent. However you can install the ""Long War Mod"" to get all the options back. Lastly, the old game made you have soldiers with psionic powers to finish the game, however, in XCOM 2, psionic soldiers are nothing but an advantage in combat. A special psionic soldier is given to you from the beggining of the last level, making your other ones nothing special from the rest of your squad. The ending was much less satisfying than the other game as well, and it seemed way easier. It did set up for XCOM 3 though which was cool.Conclusion:A really fun game that if you are new to the XCOM franchise you will definitly enjoy. However, if you have played Enemy Unknown and Enemy Within, you will notice aspects of the game that were in the old games, that you wish would be there. Overall, I would give it a 8/10"
76561198008088676,Recommended,268500,21247171,"Posted: 15 February, 2016",all,Ether Bunny,"I'm going to go with a cautious recommendation.The gameplay is solid. The visuals are good. The writing is no worse than any other large release (that is to say it doesn't make me cringe whenever people talk). The devs clearly give a damn about the community and the game's release was actually close to being a good release.Now for the cautionary notes. There are bugs. There are a LOT of bugs. Most of them aren't earth shattering or game-breaking, but they are both frequent and noticeable. An example of what I'm talking about is the weird tendency of buildings to explode when explosives are launched rather than when they explode, or a bug in which character animations sometimes cease to work after a character falls from a building. Not game breaking, but certainly immersion breaking. There are framerate drops fairly frequently (recommended settings set by game) on my computer and there's no excuse for that. There are all sorts of little niggling details that make the game harder to enjoy.Anyway, rig specs below:Intel Core i7 Haswell E OC'd at 4.0 ghzEVGA GTX 980 SC 4GB GDDR516gb DDR4 RAM OC'd at 3000Samsung 850pro SSD"
