76561198020742014,Recommended,268500,21163476,"Posted: 12 February, 2016",all,boytype,"XCOM2 is a game that is worthy of the full numbered sequel status to the original XCOM.Where XCOM:EU+EW looked to adapt the XCOM formula for a modern audiance, XCOM2 distinguishes itself from that formula through changes to both theme and gameplay.XCOM2 adds new mission types that help mix things up, adding some much needed variety to XCOM:EU's gameplay. Where XCOM:EU had basically 3 mission types (Alien Hunt, Civilian Rescue, Base/UFO Assault), XCOM2 adds VIP Escort, VIP Capture/Kill, and Press the Button  mission types, each of which has a Timed and Untimed varient. This would seemingly mean that there would be twice as much (200%!) mission variety.The number of different enemy types in XCOM2 is likewise seemingly twice as diverse. All of the aliens from the previous iteration are represented in one form or another, and a slew of newcomers join them. Many of the new enemies  require fresh tactics to be developed to deal with them, and later game additions are a refreshing sight after fighting slews of ADVENT soldiers and bots in early game.The Class system has been reworked to increase the differentiation between each classes two skill trees. There are far fewer instances where there is a CORRECT choice here (exceptions including ability to not trigger overwatch for Rangers), and the two trees are different enough except for Grenadier that you could often be taking two or three Sharpshooters, Rangers, or Specialists into a fight, each with a specialized skill set and loadout, and each useful in entirely different ways.  I say except for the Grenadier because while they do have a useful set of skills to choose from, the usefulness of OverwatcH and the fact that the grenade launcher cannot be used for it means that no matter how you spec, your Grenadier will be using his Chaingun a lot of the time. For all of the other classes the distinction is such that the gameplay for each sub-class is very different."
