76561198041374969,Recommended,268500,26720995,"Posted: 20 November, 2016",all,famouswolfe,"Overall I recommend this game, with a few asteriks**. There are many game design choices that I question and just don't feel make any sense. The core aspect of the game is still present (base management, deciding which things to build/research first, tactical missions, and that feeling of being overwhelmed), however beyond that it feels like they complicated a tried-and-true formula that is beautiful for it's simplicity. As a sequel, XCOM 2 delivers more than the original XCOM's sequel Terror From The Deep delivered. More complex, however, doesn't necessarily mean better. XCOM 2 tasks you with building a base, growing a network of resistance cells by building radio towers, R&D of alien weaponry, maintaining a small army of trained soldiers each with its own unique class and abilities, choosing which missions you will undertake each with its own rewards, and ultimately stopping the aliens. XCOM 2 limits you however, with three in-game mechanics that make it impossible to do all of those things simultaneously and forces you to choose which you will prioritize. First you have two kinds of currency: Supplies and Intel. Supplies are used to improve your base and upgrade your squad's equipment. Intel can be sold to the black market for equipment/Supplies/soldiers or can be used to see what bonuses the enemies have for one month. You have a limited amount of Supplies and Intel so obviously you have to choose wisely how you spend it. Second, there is the issue of time. The game doesn't let you just sit back to do as you please. Occasionally the game will throw missions at you which you can choose to ignore however the rewards those missions offer are absolutely critical so ignoring them is really not an option. Third, there is the Avatar project. Basically a super secret project that the aliens are working on which if completed will spell disaster for the XCOM organization. Each and every in-game month the Avatar project makes some progress, and if the meter fills up you lose. You can choose to raid alien bases which help stall the Avatar project, however it is always looming over your head. This is yet another way the game makes you feel overwhelmed, by limiting your time and forcing you to act quickly.Speaking of time, another game mechanic which both helps and hurts the game are the timed missions. In 90% of missions you undertake, there's always some objective you have to complete within a limited number of turns. No longer is it about showing up and killing all the aliens (although some missions require you to mop up remaining aliens too). You usually have to either extract a VIP at an extraction point, protect a workstation from being destroyed, destroy an alien workstation, grab some precious cargo before it self detonates, etc etc within usually 8-12 turns. This forces you to be more bold and daring in your tactics instead of just taking things nice and slow. Aliens are a lot more wary though, and sometimes can call in reinforcements if they start losing which only complicates things worse. Combined with the strict time-limit and overwhelming odds, a mission can quickly spiral out of control. This is both exciting and infuriating. I cannot tell you how many times I've been in a heated skirmish with 6 aliens and only a few precious turns to complete my objective, only to have the aliens call down reinforcements flanking my squad and completely undermine my strategy. At those moments you simply have no choice but to retreat or face losing your entire team. It may seem like the game is casually trying to screw you over, and make no mistake, it is.Overall XCOM 2 is a good game, however to me it just wasn't as good or as fun as it's predecessor, XCOM EU. The strict ground mission timers, the way the game will casually throw something at you that completely throws off your planning and strategy, the over-complex design and increased facets that you have to pay attention to, just kills the fun for me. Hopefully XCOM 3 will find a better balance."
