,Recommended,268500,21119152,"Posted: 10 February, 2016",all,endersblade,"It has its bugs and glitches, but this game is amazing.My single biggest gripe about this game is the Avatar Project countdown to doom.  XCOM does NOT belong on a time limit!  Thankfully within the first week or so of the game being out, someone basically modded it out of the game.  So I've been enjoying the game at MY pace!The graphics are a step up from EU/EW.  The customization options are better, and there are a lot more options to change.I like the direction they went with changing the aliens, and the introduction of a classic, the Snakemen, called Vipers in this game.  Though serving a different role, it's still awesome to see them!This game, overall, doesn't play the same as EU/EW.  Again, it's on a timer, and a LOT of the missions you go on have timers as well.  There are fewer aliens per mission, but what IS there is a lot more deadly.  There are no more UFOs to shoot down, which I was sad to see go, but it makes sense with how this game plays.This game is extremely moddable.  They moved a LOT of information into the .INIs, and also released a Mod Kit for the game for what can't be done in a text file.You won't really play the same game twice.  The zones you can go to on each continent change with each game, and you start on a different continent every game as well.  The bonuses for each continent are random too, which is sort of annoying because some of the bonuses are extremely useful, while some of them are almost completely worthless.Overall I'd give the base game about a 7/10, just because I HATE HATE HATE the doom clock.  With mods, this is a 9.5/10.  That 0.5 missing is from all the bugs...seriously, this game is buggy!  Mostly graphical glitches, teleporting and such, but there are some rare ones that can really bork your game.  Because of this, I caution against playing with Ironman turned on.  You may need to savescum a bit just to be able to continue playing!"
76561197968518508,Recommended,268500,26722609,"Posted: 20 November, 2016",all,[db.]Rookski,Excellent game overall. The negative reviewers clearly didn't play the early XCom games or understand this genre. I've played through 3 times and not had a single performance issue or bug.9.5/10 from me.
76561198040015820,Recommended,268500,26111030,"Posted: 18 October, 2016",all,TheSoulParadise,"It was a very long wait but after finally getting this game in my library and booting it up I instantly knew it was going to be a big step up. Without wasting your time XCOM 2 is absolutely an excellent sequel going for an alternate timeline story rather than a direct fallow up from the last game. If you enjoyed the last game have no fear about buying this one.Graphics – XCOM 2 steps up its look in a big way ditching the shell shaded cartoonish look from the last game and going for a much more detailed look with a very gritty atmosphere. Every animation, dirt stain, blood splash, and battle field has an absurd amount of love put into it allowing the player to get fully immersed in their experience.Gameplay – The basic core of the game has stayed almost the same with its turn based gameplay and full squad customization. However XCOM 2 has only added more for the player to enjoy with brand new squad classes, weapons, fully mobile base of operations, and a new stealth mechanic allowing the players squad to enter the battle field unnoticed by the enemy allowing for epic surprise attacks and crafty strategy’s to take down the alien menace. The player is going to need to make full use of these new additions as the aliens have a huge advantage over you in both numbers and technology. The game will force the player to think many turns ahead (or abuse the save feature) in order to stand a chance this time around.Story – XCOM 2s story basically revolves around the idea that you as the player were unable to stop the aliens in the first game causing an uneasy peace treaty with the aliens and earth which looks more like total subjection. You must lead the XCOM rebels to victory over the aliens by strategically attacking and disrupting their plans throughout the various countries of the world with your new mobile base. Some new faces join the team as well as a few old ones new players won’t need to play the first game to enjoy this story.Recommendation – Overall XCOM 2 is a big step up from the first game with only a few issues in the form of higher difficulty due to the constant timer put on the player causing some to feel rushed. However skilled players will be able to get powerful gear quickly evening the playing field. I would still recommend that new players finish the first game as starting with this title could cause players to ignore the first game."
