76561198111697179,Not Recommended,268500,21551126,"Posted: 29 February, 2016",all,Keyboard+Mouse,"Short Version:Enemy Unknown = Half Life 1XCOM 2 = Half Life 2If that sounds good to you, then get this game.Longer Version:First off, XCOM 2 has a fantastic premise that appropriately raises the stakes without dismissing what happened in the first game. It's much more story driven and wants to lead you down a certain path, which I personally think goes against what made EU so good. It still has the XCOM spirit of fighting a daunting, unfair, overall superior enemy, but you don't really see that at face value. It's more of a long checklist of missions, and intel. Again, if that sounds good to you, then get this game.The game is still a patch or two from being fully optimized, but I've only had the occasional dip in framerate so far. What really slows the game down is the interface, and the push for better graphics (they are MUCH better looking btw) and fancy transistions means every action takes a fraction of a second longer. Maybe that's just a nitpick, maybe it'll wear on you like it did me, I don't know.There's a handful of new ideas thrown into the game, some are insubstantial as far as I've seen, but my favorite is stealth elements. At the start of most missions, you are undetected by the aliens, and can ambush them if you're savvy enough, but that's equally hindered by the fact that almost every mission also has a timer, and I honestly don't know why that's a mechanic. It just further forces people to save-scum and go for a perfect run rather than face adversity. Just my opinion, but I hope some of you agree.It's a PC game from the ground up, to the point that gamepad controls are really messy and it doesn't respond well to analog controls (if you got a gamepad to work, please tell me how). If you've succesfully weathered the original XCOM games, this will probably make you feel right at home.I wish I could just post this as a neutral review because even though I personally don't recommend this game, there's more than enough here that most XCOM fans will love it, and I thouroghly acknowledge that. However you felt about the things I mentioned here is probably how you'll feel about them in the game, so if it's your thing, buy it."
