76561198031262604,Recommended,268500,22815582,"Posted: 5 May, 2016",all,The Bored Chairman,"Ok, I'll try to be serious with this one.Xcom2 is the sequel to Xcom: Enemy Unknown and assumes that humanity lost the war against the aliens. Most people live in Alien-run cities, under the constant vigilance of ADVENT, the Alien Peacekeeping force. Your job is to lead the remmants of the Xcom project against the Alien Overlords via tactical strike missions, which yield rewards like new personel, additional resources or minor buffs. Soon enough, the stage is set as the Aliens commence the AVATAR project (which does not filter the world in a red and blue hue, unfortunately). It's a race against the clock as you can't stop their progress, only delay it.Xcom2 brings back the famous (or infamous, depending on your views of it) RNG-based accuracy system, and further expands on it with new game mechanics like hacking (which can yield rewards, complete objectives or increase the mission difficulty, depending on the RNG). It also introduces a Dodge mechanic, meaning that units with a high Dodge stat have a chance to cut incoming damage by half.Now as for how well these mechanics mesh into the gameplay, Xcom's RNG-based accuracy offers you a chance to increase your odds of a successful shot with various abilities and items, for example, scopes, Holo-targeting, height advantage and others, meaning that it's possible to ensure that you never miss your target. Unfortunately with the hacking mechanic, you are completely reliant on RNG, even after you research better gear, as the hacking protocols for more powerful enemies are, naturally, more difficult. A specialised ammo can help lower their defenses, but for the most part, it's all down to how the RNG decides to play. Fortunately, the game can be complete without ever using this mechanic, barring objective hacking which can never fail, so you aren't forced to subject yourself to it.Now the Dodge mechanic, on the other hand, adds another layer of frustration to the game, as perfect positioning and flanking angles can result in an otherwise dead enemy to live by reducing incoming damage. This is especially frustrating when there are multiple threats with the ability to dodge. Explosive damage from grenades is undodgeable, but this forces the player to rely heavily on grenades, often dictating the squad you will field beforehand, rather than allowing the player the freedom to experiment with different items and units.Grenades themselves are a tremendous asset in this game, as opposed to the first, as they can destroy the environment and relieve enemies of their cover.  They can also create new pathes to priority objectives, useful when the objective is in a building. They shred armor and deal unavoidable damage and cannot miss, unlike rockets in Xcom: EU. However, as great as grenades are, unfortunately, their reliability makes them a must in a squad as opposed to a luxury, because why rely on RNG when you can guarantee damage? Nobody, in a practical sense, would choose RNG. And Xcom punishes those who can't make practical decisions, further cementing their place in the game as the go-to weapon of choice. There are better weapons, to be sure, but the grenade's reliability gives it the edge for best weapon in the game.Sightlines in this game seem to perform worse than before, often resulting in your support characters activating a pod while the majority of your squad is already out of moves. It's so bad that a unit standing directly next to another with vision might NOT have vision of the same enemy. Enemies will often spot you directly through walls as well, like they all have Xray vision. There are mods to help deal with this massive oversight (heh), but the fact that this made it into the final product is a real shame.The game also has its share of bugs and errors, crashes are still common, though luckily, autosave is turned on by default, so if you're like me and don't save until you're done playing, you don't have to worry about your progress.Nitpicking:This is just my personal opinion on certain game mechanics that shouldn't be present but don't adversely affect the game.1. Central Officer Bradford acts as your military advisor, and unfortunately, has gotten much more vocal since EU. Even when you turn off Beginner VO, he often repeats the same advice multiple times during a mission, which can take its toll on your patience, especially if a mission is going poorly (the last thing anybody needs after missing 3 90% shots is to be nagged at). Basically Bradford is Navi from LoZ:OoT but with better chest hair (let's see who's done their research).2. Pacing: Despite the sense of urgency implemented by the AVATAR project, the game itself feels slow, slower than EU which had no timetable. There are far too many camera swings (what is with Firaxis and cameras?), pauses in gameplay to hover over something for the sake of dialogue, and the slowmo overwatch shots, which can result in a bug where the slowmo plays for the entirety of the animation, rather than just the shot. It makes the game at times feel tedious and slow, the opposite of how a quick Guerilla Op should feel.Despite everything, however, I still recommend this game. The modding community is pretty great, and the feeling of pulling off a flawless mission just never gets old. The game may be a little rough around the edges, but it's still a great (albeit frustrating) experience."
