,Recommended,268500,21096014,"Posted: 9 February, 2016",all,Metzge,"The full review can be found onStart 2 Continue.Excerpt:It’s been a while since I’ve been legitimately excited about a game’s release. In fact, despite the glorious technological advances of the 21st century, the only thing that would’ve made my day first trying out XCOM 2 any better that satisfying experience of the cellophane wrap tearing as you claw at the game disc, that new game smell flooding your nostrils like some savage beast. But alas, Steam patched that all out a while ago and I’m a sucker for the kind of instant gratification digital retailing provides. It’s the very opposite (that being, latent gratification, I guess) that attracts me to XCOM 2 like a planet of derpy sentients with a poorly funded space program attracts an imperialistic alien race that regards abductions, gene splicing, and human target practice among its nobler pursuits.Twenty years have gone by and your attempts back in XCOM: Enemy Unknown were all for naught: the aliens have won and teamed up with the collaborator turncoats among your species, bringing about the ADVENT, a puppet government that lulls the unsuspecting into a false sense of security while the alien occupiers are free to snatch up test subjects and declare martial law as they see fit, all under the friendly guise of the one they call “The Speaker.”"
76561198018670246,Recommended,268500,21142526,"Posted: 11 February, 2016",all,Alinahlis,"Words fail me honestly. I was extremely nervous that this game wouldn't be able to live up to enemy unknown. I am also exstatic that I was so very wrong, to those of you who were fans of enemy unknown, this game is better in almost every possible way."
76561198041003571,Recommended,268500,25410329,"Posted: 8 September, 2016",all,darazel2001,"XCOM 2 is much in the spirit of its predecessor, XCOM: Enemy Unknown from 2012. For everyone who did not play that game, please skip to the next paragraph. If you played it: XCOM 2 is more polished, more diverse and prettier. It experiments with some new concepts like timed missions and concealment. This makes changes in strategy necessary. Personally, I highly enjoyed this. It is also more difficult. If you liked XCOM: Enemy Unknown, you will like this, but you'll need to adapt a little bit. I do not think that you will be disappointed.If you have not played XCOM: Enemy Unknown: XCOM 2 is a turn-based tactical game where you lead a small number of soldiers (generally 4-6) into missions against alien forces occupying earth. Combat is well-designed and missions take about 15 to 40 minutes, depending on your play style. Your soldiers will gain experience and level up in one of five different classes (only four available at the beginning of each game, and a sixth becoming available with one DLC) which will grant them increased stats and additional abilities (as chosen by you from two alternatives per level). Part of the game is making the different classes work well together. You will be able to customize your soldiers  appearance. The available mission types are diverse enough (rescue, kill everything, destroy device, protect device, defend base, protect civilians…) and maps are created randomly so things won’t become boring too quickly (I’ve clocked nearly 90 hours at the moment and am still highly entertained, even without looking into mods).Supplementing the tactical simulation is a strategic layer that features some base building, researching, budget organisation and mission selection. You will have to succeed at the tactical and the strategic level, since one will fall apart without the other. This aspect of the game is interesting enough, but the focus is more on the combat.The difficulty level is harder that one might expect, and I recommend beginners to start on the lowest difficulty setting. From there, it will take some time to master the game, but having one campaign on the lowest difficulty under the belt will open up the more advanced difficulties.I have mixed feelings about the DLCs. ‘Shen’s Gift’ and its content is arguably the best and I can fully recommend it. ‘Alien Hunter’ adds interesting new opponents (with a whole new mechanic regarding the turn system) that are a nice challenge for experienced players. I would not recommend this to someone new to the game, and at places the ‘flavour’ is also a bit non-fitting to the setting. The ‘Anarchy’s Children’ DLC is only about new optics for your soldiers, so if that is something you like, go ahead. It won’t add any real game content.All in all, this is a fantastic game, although there are some bugs to be aware of, especially in regards to line-of-sight. Still, I can fully recommend XCOM 2. It gives you a great time for the money you spend, and afterwards you can still modify the hell out of it with the available mods (which I haven’t even done yet). Have played it a great deal, will continue to do so. 9/10"
