76561198000785358,Not Recommended,268500,21372001,"Posted: 21 February, 2016",all,TheCombatWombat,"I'll be honest... I LOVED XCOM:EU. So much so that I've completed it multiple times, including on Impossible/Ironman, and on Long War. Everything I saw in the build up to XCOM 2 said that I should love it just as much. But I didn't, and for most of the time, I'm not even sure WHY I don't like it. An accumulation of little things, I think.For one thing, the story is based on the ""it was all a dream"" premise. In XCOM 2, the aliens won and everything you experienced from early mid-game in XCOM:EU was actually taking place in an alien simulation, as they pull tactical info and doctrine from your brain. I hate feeling like everything I did and achieved in XCOM:EU was wasted.For another, they've implemented a turn-counter on many missions that make success or failure into a largely luck-based affair. If you're lucky, the pods are spread out, you can avoid some activations, and you'll succeed at the mission. If you're unlucky, the pods are all in/around the objective, and you'll have to fight them all which is likely to lead to soldier deaths and/or mission failure.I was attached to my troopers in XCOM:EU, and I liked the classes. In XCOM 2, I just can't find the same level of attachment, nor do I like the classes as much. The Ranger is basically the Assault, but with a melee attack (which is minimally useful, unless you LIKE being out of cover right next to the enemy). The Sniper remains the sniper. The Grenadier is basically a weaksauce Heavy - Why the hell are you carrying a magazine-fed 'nade launcher, and only loading two of the six chambers?! Max two rockets, I could understand, those buggers are heavy... max two 'nades? Not so much. Sure, I know it's for ""balance"" reasons, but I'd rather have cool than balanced. And don't get me started on the Support - I detest the new hacking minigame. They could have done something really good, but instead, it's just another RNG roll.In addition, many of the aliens are sporting new abilities, some of which are complete BS. Just one example is the Viper's tongue-grab. They can pull your dudes out of cover into the open, from ridiculously long distances, with near guaranteed hits (I've never seen a miss, although I have seen some YouTubers get some), which pulls you into a grapple for a guaranteed 3 damage, continuing to the next round unless you can succeed at 30%-40% shots. Screw that.I'm sure there will be some ""Git Guds"" in response to this review, but they can sod right off. I found the game actively unpleasant to play, and frequently found myself feeling that the game was unfair - and that's coming from a dude who beat XCOM:EU on I/I, and never found it to be as unfair feeling as XCOM2. So take this for what it is.... I didn't enjoy XCOM2. If you have no problems with the issues I raised, you might. I certainly encourage you to try."
