,Recommended,268500,34658113,Posted: 1 September,all,Navarro,"I was skeptical about XCOM2. The notion that the alien won the war lead me to suspect the game was taking a dramatically new direction, and I wasn't sure that the developer could do so effectively. There was no underground base anymore: you're on a ship, travelling from region to region - even that worried me. When I saw that the game was no longer ""spooky"" or intimidating, I was very much dissapointed. When I saw many of the enemies had been reimagined, I was troubled again. When I saw that completely new enemies had been created, which look less classic alien lore than they do irrational scifi fantasy molded to appeal to teenagers (Shieldbearer, Avatar), I was greatly concerned.Watching gameplay, I observed that units look more like teenage fashion models than soldiers. That the customization options concentrated on teenage apparel and exotic fantasy appeareances. There were no standard kevlar helmets, but there were dozens of mohawks to choose from. I saw that the game's launch was plagued by bugs. I saw that the DLC concentrated on additional non-militaristic apparel, and ""rulers"" who were players weren't entertained by but instead immensely frustrated with, to the point of disabling the DLC which they had purchased. I saw the mission timers and was frustrated by the idea of being forced to abandon the tactics of scouting and bounding in favor of sprinting blindly into the unknown, because there's no time. I saw the doomsday clock, wasn't sure what it was about or how to deal with it - it was less straight-forward than the previous XCOM incarnation. I saw the immense number of complaints in the forum, and I saw the developer responding to many of those complaints with bans, not solutions. I was very worried that the game was bad, and that it wasn't going to be improved.Then I saw the game on sale, at a substantial discount. I hadn't even played the game, but I felt that I already disliked it. I decided to give XCOM 2 a fair chance. I bought the game. After installing and starting XCOM 2, it crashed on the strategy screen, before even my first mission. That was absolutely not the last crash. I found myself disappointed again and again. ""Soldier"" appearances were even worse than I had I believed. Graduating beyond the basic gear, the armors and weapons look increasingly ridiculous, and are unmistakably ridiculous by the final tiers. Mods were absolutely necessary to remedy this, because with all the DLC offered, it was apparently never thought to offer realistic kits beyond the basic gear.In a game of tactical warfare, emphasizing the use of cover and concealment, one would think a larger emphasis would be placed on gear which looks like what you might expect the soldiers of the future to wear. After all, several counties are already developing full armor suits, combat robots and so forth - one need only look at these publically viewable protoypes to estimate what the future of combat will look like. Instead, they abandoned realistic gear and camoflage for elaborate fantasy appearances, with even an assortment of lights on their gear to ensure any enemy would see their soldiers long before the player's soldiers see the enemy. Instead of looking at military gear for inspiration, they looked at Fallout, teenage fashion and cartoons.None of the improvements I would have expected were present. An entirely different direction was pursued. The developers didn't increase the spooky atmosphere to an experience of sheer horror, but the spookiness was instead abandoned entirely. They didn't better embrace alien lore to produce enemies with appearances and behavior comparable to the decades of UFO/abduction reports, or classic alien films. They didn't offer a uniform manager, so that, as military organizations do, the player could quickly equip every member of his/her squad with the same appearance - a uniform. Luckily, there's a mod for that. The game doesn't inform the user of the environment the squad will be deployed into, so that appropriate camoflage can be utilized. Luckily there's a mod for that too. They didn't make it so that there's bonuses based on the camoflage/colors used in unit appearances, for example a concealment bonus when wearing black at night. There's no reconnaissance drone allowing for constistent observation of the battlefield, despite that the game's Gremlin drones could have offered such a capacity very easily, and in fact nearly do - except the Gremlin can only surveil once per operation. Being able to scout ahead consistently via UAV would have been a great improvement. Luckily, there's a mod for this.In general, the story's short and it's not very interesting. The ending is disappointing, but I won't spoil that. However. The game is very familiar. It's also entertaining. With the aid of mods, one can overcome the majority of this title's shortcomings. There will still be crashes. You can even mod out the doomsday clock and battle timers, but I've found they're nothing to worry about. I've never lost a battle because of running out of time, and I've never lost the game because of the doomsday clock, or at all, for that that matter. The maps are now generated randomly, which means that sometimes they will be greatly unbalanced, if not impossible. I've played at least one impossible map, where after landing my soldiers, I was surrounded by an extensive horde of powerful enemies. Three ""pods,"" to be exact. They each had cover nearby. My soldiers didn't. It was near the beginning of the game. It was, I believe, four squadies kitted with basic gear, standing in the open, with no cover available, against nine entrenched adversaries, in the first turn, on Rookie difficulty. I've played several battles which were ridiculous, on Rookie, Veteran and Commander difficulty, but that none were ever as bad as that one. Many were difficult, but none were impossible, aside from the one which I just described.If you're skeptical about XCOM 2, don't be. It's very similar to the previous incarnations and if you enjoyed those, you'll like this. Whether or not the DLCs are worth buying, however, is another question entirely. Definitely buy the base game. If the game's bundled at an amazing discount, then go for the bundle. You can disable to DLC if you find that it's frustrating for you, or you can avoid the leaders without disabling the DLC by never bothering them in the ""nest"" mission. They won't appear in any of your battles if you don't. If you're a fashion minded teenager or a kid who things gothic style weapons are cool, then the DLC is definitely for you. The base game is definitely worth buying for anyone who was interested enough to read this full review. If you read all of this, I guarantee you won't regret buying this XCOM 2. It's fun, despite its many problems."
